sessions.sessionName: Poster Session 1

sessions.sessionDescription: The Day 1 Plenary brings into focus the vast returns on investment in family planning both locally and globally. Two roundtable discussions will take place followed by a Q&A period with questions from the live and virtual audiences. The first roundtable includes invited discussants Dr. Uzziel Ndagijimana, Minister of Finance and Economic Planning of Rwanda; Dr. Ernesto Pernia, Director of National Economic and Development Authority of the Phillippines; and Kate Hampton, CEO of the Children’s Investment Fund Foundation. This discussion will highlight the role of policies, practice, for effective investment in family planning to reap the demographic dividend. The second roundtable includes invited discussants Dr. Hans-Peter Kohler of the University of Pennsylvania and Ms. Jane Nyathi, a selected ICFP youth leader who is a District Facilitator with FHI360 Zimbabwe. The second roundtable will explore returns on investment in family planning related to health, finance, security, and the environment. The discussions will be moderated by Dr. Chris Elias, President of the Global Development Division of the Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation.

presentations.title: Overview of Guttmacher-Lancet Commission Report on Sexual and Reproductive Health and Rights: A New Definition and Agenda
The Costs and Benefits of Investing in Sexual and Reproductive Health and Rights
Reaching the Tech Generation
Connecting Sexual and Reproductive Health and Rights to Humanitarian Response

sessions.sessionDescription:
Gaps in sexual and reproductive health and rights (SRHR) take an enormous toll on individuals, communities and economies around the world. Closing these gaps requires a holistic approach that encompasses the rights of all individuals to make decisions about their bodies—free of stigma, discrimination and coercion—and to have access to essential package of comprehensive and high-quality sexual and reproductive health interventions.

In May, the Guttmacher-Lancet Commission released a new vision for how to achieve universal access to SRHR, one that is affordable, attainable and essential to the achievement of health, equitable development and human rights for all. The Commission called on governments, UN agencies, civil society organizations and other key stakeholders to adopt this new, comprehensive definition of SRHR that integrates the full range of people’s needs and services including those that are rarely recognized or addressed in global discussions, such as abortion, infertility and adolescent sexuality. This definition offers a universal framework to guide stakeholders in developing policies, services and programs that address all aspects of SRHR effectively and appropriately.

Turning this vision into reality will require continued and expanded investment in successful interventions such as providing contraceptive services and maternal and newborn care, and prevention and treatment of HIV/AIDS and other STIs and new efforts to address services that have been neglected. It will also require greater collaboration across fields; generating new evidence to understand the needs of those most often left out of policy and program discussions; sustained advocacy and investment to advance and implement favorable laws and policies; and commitment to change social norms that often exclude those most vulnerable from access to health care.

This panel will discuss the report recommendations, highlight the costs and benefits of investing in SRHR, and explore new areas for research, policy, advocacy and programs that work towards advancing this new SRHR agenda.  Participants can expect a robust and engaging panel discussion followed by an open dialogue among the audience and panelists. The panelists will consist of two Commissioners, a youth advocate on the need to leverage technology and creativity to reach young people, and a health expert working to integrate SRHR care, including counselling for gender-based violence, into refugee camps.

presentations.title: How do we know what works? Building a framework for cross-sector, inter-disciplinary evaluation and research to maximise the impact of integrated family planning programming

sessions.sessionDescription:
Objectives:

to present data and experiences of multi-sector, multi-level responses to interconnected population, environment and livelihoods challenges in Ethiopia and Uganda; to present novel advocacy and research strategies to demonstrate the necessity of multi-disciplinary, multi-sector approaches to promoting family planning within complex development settings; to challenge participants to understand the interconnections between sectors that are necessary to promote family planning in the context of the SDGs; to debate what research, policy and practice responses can be developed, adapted and scaled to build on current experiences to promote family planning in the context of the SDGs.

Description:

Cross-sector linkages between anthropogenic climate change, environmental sustainability, population growth and mobility, and human and ecosystem health are increasingly evident and pose significant development challenges (Crist et al. 2017 Science; Aukema et al. 2017 PlosOne; Newman et al 2015 RepHlthMatters). Current population dynamics, including natural population growth (fuelled by lack of access to, and use of, contraception), economic and stress- and conflict-driven migration, frequently overwhelm the capacity of governments and development efforts to make progress towards achieving the SDGs. Core to progress, family planning investments can offer multiple returns across multiple sectors if they are integrated into cross-sector programming. Yet, the necessary multi-sector approaches remain elusive. This session provides an analysis of integrated approaches to programmes and partnerships that are being implemented in Ethiopia and Uganda and critical reflections on advocacy and multi-disciplinary research efforts to maximise cross-sector implementation efforts.  The target audience is practitioners, academics, NGOs, think tanks, activists and policy makers at national, regional and global levels. This session takes up core conference themes in Track 1 and Track 9 and brings empirical evidence and practical experiences to bear on central debates of how to meaningfully implement and evaluate multi-sector responses to promote investments in family planning in creative ways and to maximise the returns on those investments.

Research/program/policy implications:

Findings and lessons from this session underline the importance of cross-sector action to address dual interrelated goals of expanded access to family planning, particularly for last-mile communities, and sustainable development through protecting natural resources. Integrated programming, and multi-disciplinary evaluation, are critical for promoting FP2020 goals, contributing meaningfully to SDG attainment, and significantly expanding access to the benefits of family planning, not only for human health but also for habitat protection and ecosystem health. In this way, returns on family planning investments will be truly maximised for future generations.

Medical abortion self-use in low and middle income countries: a systematic mapping of evidence

sessions.sessionDescription:
Panel objectives

A high quality, rights-based approach to family planning must include a range of contraceptive methods, that can be used and discontinued per the needs of the client, and abortion services.  The presentations on this panel will review currently available data and identify priority research and monitoring gaps for four methods of contraception and abortion that are growing as a share of family planning programs; contraceptive implants, emergency contraception, DMPA sub-cutaneous injection (DMPA-SC), and medical abortion. 

Description

Providing access to a wide variety of family planning methods, including short- and long-acting contraceptive methods and abortion services, is critical to meeting the needs of women and providing high quality care.   With the introduction of new methods and/or the scale-up of low prevalence methods within a country, new research and monitoring needs arise. Along with effectively monitoring coverage and uptake, questions surrounding user preferences, service environment limitations, including removal of long-acting methods, and barriers to access are critical to answer to ensure methods can be introduced and scaled-up successfully.

This panel will feature four speakers who will discuss a range of questions related to the introduction and scale-up of new or under-utilized methods.

  • Gwen Morgan, USAID E2A Project, will present results from a study in Mozambique examining the burdens and benefits of collecting additional information related to IUD and implant removal and determining the feasibility of producing useful and actionable data.
  • Elizabeth Larson, PMA2020 (Performance Monitoring and Accountability 2020), will present on how different definitions of current EC use influence the method prevalence rate, modern method prevalence rate, and method mix across nine-countries in sub-Saharan Africa and recommend how to define and measure EC use for effective program monitoring.
  • Jennifer Drake, PATH, will review the currently available evidence base on DMPA-SC and self-injection in order to help clarify research and evaluation questions that should be prioritized by donors, governments, and implementers.
  • Ernestina Coast, LSE, will review the evidence base regarding how women seek and receive information about self-use of abortion in low and middle income countries and will identify key research gaps, and the data and evidence needed to fill these gaps.

The session will be chaired by Linnea Zimmerman, Associate Director of Research, PMA2020.

IMPLICATIONS

Using current data and evidence assists policy and program implementers in successfully incorporating new and under-utilized methods to expand method choice, while identifying and prioritizing remaining research gaps can guide the development of new and ongoing measurement strategies.

presentations.title: Adding it up:  Comparing country-level cost benefit analysis on contraceptive investments
Using evidence to inform rights-based advocacy on family planning in Rwanda
Investing in contraceptive in practice: the Ouagadougou Partnership experience.
Evidence-based action:  Creating and prioritizing effective programs and policies to meet women’s reproductive health needs

sessions.sessionDescription:
Over 200 million women in Africa, Asia and Latin America and the Caribbean want to avoid pregnancies, but are not using modern contraception.  Recent research from the Guttmacher Institute explores the far-reaching benefits of meeting women’s contraceptive needs in several countries.   Findings show that improving contraceptive access and services can reduce direct health expenditures (related to pregnancy, delivery, abortion and newborn care) and social costs including maternal and perinatal deaths and DALYs.  Investing in contraception may also have indirect advantages such as improving women’s educational attainment and workforce participation, ultimately benefitting individual families, the economy and society as a whole.

Using this country-level information, ministries of health, women’s health advocates, NGOs and development agencies can identify the needs of women locally and funnel the appropriate resources, via policies and programs directed on reproductive health. Meeting these needs requires government agencies to focus both on ensuring adequate contraceptive supplies and reaching women with unmet need, particularly in vulnerable populations. 

This panel presents evidence on the tangible benefits of meeting the contraceptive needs of women at the country-level, offers perspectives on how to prioritize women’s health, especially among vulnerable subpopulations, and strategizes ways governments can feasibly improve women’s health outcomes by funneling investments in contraceptive care.

Panel Objectives:

  • Illustrate how investing in meeting women’s contraceptive needs can improve individual health and socioeconomic outcomes and benefit the health sector by averting medical costs associated with unintended pregnancies. 
  • Emphasize reproductive health services as essential healthcare and strategize practical ways for advocates to use cost-benefit data to influence policymakers to focus on meeting women’s contraceptive needs, particularly among vulnerable populations.
  • Offer perspectives on how research can be used to prioritize reproductive health in Ministry of Health budgets and to create evidence-based policies to improve health outcomes.

Research, program and policy implications:

Several implications arise from examining the costs and benefits of investing in meeting women’s unmet need for contraception.   Research presented in this panel is at the country-level with some regional and poverty breakdowns, though often programs are focused on small areas or populations within a country.   Panelists will discuss how large, broad data can be used to help inform programs and policies nationally as well as locally.  Government investments in contraception may bring modest immediate fiscal savings, but can offer broad long-term benefits and therefore, policies and programs focusing on women’s health should be implemented and evaluated with this in mind.

sessions.sessionDescription:
Compared to Anglophone Africa, Francophone countries have the highest rates of maternal and child mortality, the highest fertility rates, and lowest contraceptive prevalence rates. To address these developmental issues (which often times impact young women the most) there has been an increasingly large youth movement assuming leadership roles in SRHR advocacy regionally.

As international organizations, donors, and governments are looking to address the specific needs of young people in francophone Africa, young advocates are in turn looking to speak to the issues of their peers, and offer youth led solutions. This panel's objectives will be for young advocates to share advocacy and programmatic wins, challenges, and lessons learned coming from youth-led SRHR efforts across the Ouagadougou Partnership (OP) countries. We want this to be an interactive panel for peer to peer exchanges, AND a space to provide insight to adult allies to better meaningfully engage with young advocates. To do so panelists will share:

  • Advocacy goals and messages

  • Challenges faced

  • Success stories

  • Best practices in meaningfully engaging with young advocates

This panel will give a glimpse into the lived experiences of young SRHR advocates in francophone Africa, and open up discussion around what adult allies (from governments to donors) can do to further support their work. This will not only be presentations on successes and challenges, but a rare opportunity for francophone advocates to exchange and utilize each other as resources to advance advocacy and programmatic SRHR goals. The panel will thus be structured as such:

Flash-presentations: How has youth led advocacy played out in francophone Africa?

  • Youth Mission for Education, Health, Solidarity and Inclusion, Cote d’Ivoire

  • International Youth Alliance for Family Planning, DRC and Togo

  • Ouagadougou Partnership Young Ambassadors, Burkina Faso

  • Population Works Africa, Washington, DC

Rotating Hack-a-thons: One representative from each above stated organization will sit in a corner of the rooms and lead a 10-15 min conversation on the following topics:

  • How to mobilize young advocates for policy and behavior change (IYAFP, DRC)

  • How to leverage your network of adult allies for maximum impact (OP YAs, Burkina Faso)

  • How to communicate with decision makers for policy impact (MESSI, Cote d’Ivoire)

  • Insights for adult allies into meaningful youth engagement (PopWorks, DC)

These conversations will be based on the experiences of the young advocate leading the discussion; but will focus heavily on questions/comments from participants (peer to peer exchanges.)

sessions.sessionDescription:
Panel Objectives

  • Gain a better understanding of reasons for unmet need for contraception with a focus on method-specific beliefs and fertility preferences in resource-constrained settings.
  • Highlight factors influencing method choice, discontinuation and switching in the context of limited method mix.
  • Define family planning program interventions that could enhance client choice, minimize discontinuation and reduce unmet need for contraception in resource-constrained settings.

    • Panel Description

    There has been remarkable progress in expanding the availability and use of modern family methods in low and middle-income countries (LMICs) over the past four decades. There, however, persist wide variations in modern contraceptive prevalence rate (mCPR) between and within LMICs. As of 2015, for instance, mCPR was more than two times higher in Asia (62%) and Latin America and the Caribbean (67%) than in sub-Saharan Africa (24%). Unmet need for contraception was, on the other hand, more than two times higher in sub-Saharan Africa (24%) than in Asia (10%) or Latin America and the Caribbean (11%). Within sub-Saharan Africa, estimates from the most recent Demographic and Health Surveys (DHS) show that mCPR ranged from 3% in Central African Republic to 66% in Zimbabwe while unmet need for contraception ranged from 10% in Zimbabwe to 38% in Angola. Literature shows that uptake of modern methods in LMICs is partly influenced by myths and misconceptions about contraception. There is, however, limited understanding of how these myths and misconceptions affect choice of particular methods. In addition, the method mix in many of these settings is dominated by a few methods. In sub-Saharan Africa, injectables and pills have been the dominant methods for a long time although uptake of implants has been on the rise during the past five to ten years. The proposed panel brings together evidence from different settings of LMICs that improves our understanding of the extent to which method-specific beliefs and fertility preferences influence choice, discontinuation, and switching in the context of limited method mix.

    Program implications

    The evidence contributes to the current global discourse on the importance of improving method mix and addressing discontinuation in order to sustain or improve further mCPR in settings that have made remarkable progress in uptake and to bring in new users in settings that are still lagging behind if the commitment of reaching 120 million women with unmet need by the year 2020 is to be realized.

presentations.title: Understanding the problem: What do we know about implant users’ access to removal services?
Expanding access to removal-inclusive LARC services in the community, experience and recommendations from Ethiopia
Expanding access to implant removal services at the facility level, evidence and recommendations from Uganda and Kenya
Understanding LARC removal behaviour: lessons from MSI research and client data in Zimbabwe

sessions.sessionDescription:
Panel Objectives:

  • Present evidence on the status of implant removal accessibility around the world, and highlight remaining learning and information gaps.
  • Provide critical recommendations for family planning programmers, donors, and policy makers that address how to expand implant removal service access in various settings, including at the community level, at facilities, and through various other service delivery channels.
  • Orient participants to the products newly available through the K4Health Implant Removal Resources page of the Implants Toolkit, with brief examples of their use.
  • Deliver a “Call to Action” for governments, donors and implementing partners to implement recommendations.

    • Description: With contraceptive implant uptake on the rise, governments, family planning programs, and other stakeholders (including users themselves) are eager to ensure that access to quality removal services are within reach for clients using implants. Emerging data demonstrate that this accessibility has not been achieved. The Implant Removal Task Force, with representatives from 20 institutions, has over the past 2+ years identified the most prominent and common gaps in implant removal services and convened regularly to address these gaps through experience sharing, advocacy, and the development of critical resources. These resources, now available on K4Health, span a variety of purposes: job aids for providers, data briefs for advocates, a learning agenda and research tools for researchers, equipment and supplier lists for program managers, and more. To enable stakeholders to adopt these resources, panelists will highlight these tools and how they’ve been used, while sharing their deeper insights on how programming can truly be adapted through a “removal-inclusive” lens. So too will participants be invited to share their insights on how universal access to removal can be achieved. The panelists represent a variety of projects funded by various donors, and will share experience from around the world.

    Research/program/policy implications: Participants will walk away with clear, evidence based recommendations that they can employ in their own family planning work to adapt programs and policies in order to expand access to quality implant removal services. For example, those engaged in provider capacity building will hear about best practices for mobilizing implant removal clients during training events and the need for targeted refresher courses on side effect management and removal. Those providing implants in community settings, whether CHWs or outreach, will learn how partners are building programs in a way that ensures clients don’t face disproportionate barriers attempting to access removal services.

sessions.sessionDescription:
Objectives         

  • To understand the importance and relevance of client expectations, preferences, and feedback in programs and research in addressing quality of care
  • To highlight three approaches to gathering and applying these client perspectives in different contexts
  • To link client perspectives to efforts to improve quality of care

Description       

Despite decades of emphasis on quality of care, attention to the expectations, preferences, and perspectives of clients has been often missing from the discussions. We know that client expectations and experiences matter to contraceptive adoption, use, and continuation, and that expectations also influence satisfaction with services. This panel is important because it unpacks this dimension of quality of care, drawing on recent research and interventions in several contexts and using different methodologies.

The three presentations will look, first, at the preferences of women for counselling content and provider-client interaction, which provide insights into improving quality and satisfaction with counseling; second, at the influences of past experiences and experiences of neighbors and friends on decisions about contraceptive choice and sources of service; and, third, at the experiences of young people empowered to assess and give feedback on youth-friendly services as a critical component of improving quality of care. 

Taken together these three projects provide a rich understanding of what matters to family planning users, how experiences that live up to, or fail to live up to, expectations can affect choices and use of family planning, and how clients themselves are able to make a difference in what care is provided and how.  These presentations draw on largely recent experiences from India, Ethiopia, and Malawi, but their lessons are globally relevant.

The moderator, a leading funder of quality of care initiatives, will frame the panel’s theme focusing on the critical importance of understanding and addressing client perspectives and draw out similarities and differences in findings across settings that point to avenues for future research and program implementation.

Implications  

As FP/RH programs increasingly look to implementing nuanced quality of care approaches, understanding and addressing what matters to clients is crucial. Looking across these results shows there are promising and diverse approaches to gathering insights from clients (and potential clients) that can be turned into concrete research and programmatic follow-up to improve quality of care. By providing tangible examples, this panel will catalyze interest in investing in ways to capture all aspects of client experiences both to increase quality of care provided and to maximize the impact of current investments in family planning programs.
sessions.sessionName: Living up to Expectations? Exploring Client Perspectives and Experiences to Improve Quality of Care

sessions.sessionDescription:
Panel objectives

This panel will 1) describe effective strategies for providing comprehensive family planning services during acute emergencies and 2) explore the implications for revised humanitarian guidelines that include FP as part of the minimum package of reproductive health services in acute settings. From the Pacific to Bangladesh to Yemen and Uganda, no woman or girl should be denied feasible, necessary and, most importantly, lifesaving contraceptive services.

Description

For the past few years, the Interagency Working Group on Reproductive Health in Crisis (IAWG), a coalition of key health organizations, has worked to strengthen family planning programs in humanitarian settings and make the case for prioritizing family planning as part of the minimum package of services offered at the onset of a crisis. Through these efforts, IAWG has revised the Minimum Initial Service Package (MISP) for RH in crises– a set of priority interventions designed to save lives and avert preventable injuries, illness and suffering, particularly among women and girls, at the onset of a crisis – to include a focused objective to prevent unintended pregnancies. Its inclusion as a lifesaving health service in acute crises ensures that all possible methods of contraception, including long-acting methods, be offered in crisis settings so women and girls can truly have choice.

The International Rescue Committee, CARE, Save the Children, and IPPF support MISP responses in humanitarian settings throughout the world. Family planning is an essential pillar of these responses. Presenters will describe successes, challenges and lessons learned from responses in some of the hardest places to work and offer recommendations for how other humanitarian organizations can effectively reduce unintended pregnancies in crises.

Implications

This panel contributes to the growing evidence base and existing guidelines, like the revised MISP, for the necessary inclusion of the entire range of family planning methods at the onset of crisis.

sessions.sessionDescription:
Objectives: This panel session will showcase several approaches being championed by various organizations that aim to address existing gaps in reproductive health services for the urban poor. It will highlight how these organizations are partnering with many local governments to bring about better access to family planning (FP) services in slums and peri-urban communities. It will discuss how proven FP strategies have been adapted to the local urban context and are now demonstrating impact on the ground.

Description: The United Nations projects that by 2050, nearly 70% of the world’s population will be urban, with 90% of that urbanization occurring in Asia and Africa. Almost all that growth will be concentrated in poor urban settlements. Slum dwellers have considerably worse health outcomes compared to their wealthier urban counterparts, and in some places even worse health outcomes than rural residents. It is likely that increased urbanization will only exacerbate this disparity. As urbanization marches on, there is a pressing need to ensure that the urban poor are not forgotten.

In policy circles, much attention has been given to addressing urban challenges like crime, traffic congestion, poor sanitation, and pollution. However, approaches that tackle the reproductive health needs of the urban poor are lacking. Due to limited knowledge of and access to modern contraceptive methods, the urban poor have less agency over their sexual and reproductive health. Most of them end up providing for a large family, putting a strain on their financial resources, compromising their quality of life and reducing their chances of escaping poverty. Providing women and their partners the means to choose the number and spacing of their children would have a substantial positive impact to their family and communities.

Program implications: This panel session will offer practical guidance on the crucial components of FP strategies that work in urban poor settings. It will help inform program efforts geared towards delivering the SDG promise of “mak[ing] cities and human settlements inclusive, safe, resilient and sustainable.

sessionChairs.company: Margaret Pyke Trust, with the Population & Sustainability Network

sessions.sessionDescription:
Objectives

This panel will highlight how family planning (FP) contributes to broader development goals such as resilience, improved livelihoods, environmental conservation, and sustainable use of natural resources, and demonstrate why FP is relevant for making progress towards those goals. Panelists representing four organizations operating in multiple countries will highlight how FP adds value and enhances equity for people in last-mile communities, in alignment with FP2020 goals. Panelists will provide insights on the return on investment of integrated interventions, using data-driven evidence at both the global level and from project sites, including Population, Health, and Environment (PHE) projects in Madagascar, South Africa, and Tanzania. Recognition of the value of voluntary FP for broader development goals in non-health sectors is an effective way to achieve sexual and reproductive health and rights (SRHR) for more people, while enhancing development outcomes across multiple sectors.

Description

The panel will present on the return on investment of FP for building resilience, enabling women to balance their productive and reproductive roles to undertake sustainable livelihoods, furthering environmental objectives through female empowerment and more broadly. The panel will present research and development models that highlight the pathways between FP and these non-health development priorities.

Example PHE projects will illuminate the value FP provides for sustainable livelihoods, income generation and environmental conservation outcomes. These projects demonstrate how the integration of community-based reproductive health services with conservation initiatives can be a win-win approach for community and ecosystem health.

Insights will be shared demonstrating what can motivate environmental conservation organizations to incorporate FP within their projects, and how analyzing population dynamics creates a strong rationale for doing so. 

Research/program/policy implications

This panel demonstrates how and why non-health sectors, including resilience, livelihoods, and conservation, are increasingly recognizing the value of FP for their work. Integrated programming contributes to and reinforces the work of the population and reproductive health community. Raising awareness of the value of voluntary FP in non-health sectors will create new champions and potential funding sources for SRHR, helping to attain FP2020 goals and the Sustainable Development Goals, enhancing equity within last-mile communities.

presentations.title: Inclusive access to health services for children and youth with disabilities
Addressing barriers to the enjoyment of SRHR and treatment of HIV for young persons with disabilities
Reducing stigma and ensuring accessible reproductive health services for youth with disabilities in Nairobi's urban slums
Including persons with disabilities in SRH programmes in rural Kenya

sessions.sessionDescription: An estimated 180 to 200 million people with disabilities globally are between the ages of 10 and 24.  Adolescents and young persons with disabilities have the same sexual and reproductive health needs and rights as their non-disabled peers.  Yet too often those needs go unmet due to a variety of factors, such as a lack of accessible SRH services, limited personal autonomy, and a lack of empowerment, which can be exacerbated by a lack of education. The ICPD Programme of Action calls on states to recognise the rights of all adolescents, including adolescents and young people with disabilities, to ‘appropriate direction and guidance in sexual and reproductive matters’, and to ensure they have access to the services and information they need to live healthy and fulfilling lives.  Each of the organizations represented on the panel is taking steps to advocate for the rights of young people with disabilities to enjoy sexual and reproductive health, and support inclusive access to comprehensive sexuality education for young people with disabilities.  They were each participants in a forthcoming global study conducted for UNFPA as part of the WE DECIDE campaign, a global programme to support the efforts of young people with disabilities to have their voices heard and increase their visibility to policymakers.  The panelists will speak to current research by their organizations on the barriers faced by adolescents and youth with disabilities seeking SRH services as well as best practices in ensuring young people with disabilities are included in programmes designed to achieve the full enjoyment of sexual and reproductive health and rights for all. The panel consists of three organizations whose missions include advocating for the rights of persons with disabilities, including reproductive health rights, and two who offer programs on SRHR for young people that are inclusive of young persons with disabilities.  The panel is designed to represent the twin-track model called for by the CRPD, recognizing that full inclusion requires both a mainstreaming strategy that includes persons with disabilities in policies and programmes relevant to SRH, and a disability-specific strategy that includes developing and implementing disability-specific laws, policies, and programme activities designed for the purpose of promoting the sexual and reproductive health and rights of persons with disabilities when particular supports are required. The panelists also work in diverse contexts and have expertise in reaching those most marginalized, such as in Kenya's remote rural communities and Nairobi's urban slums, as well as developing effective partnerships with government entities.

presentations.title: Enhancing competencies of medical and midwifery graduates for provision of contraception and abortion in a pre-service training
Role of simulation-based training in advancing skills in provision of contraception and abortion services: Experience from Bahir Dar School of Medicine, Ethiopia
‘Michu’ model of Women-centered Family planning and Comprehensive abortion care in a teaching hospital
Implementing Quality Improvement (QI) Projects to Enhance Contraception and Abortion Care Services and Pre-Service Training at Adama General Hospital and Medical College

sessions.sessionDescription:
Panel objectives

The panel posits that integration of competency-based contraception and comprehensive abortion care (CAC) training into pre-service health education is an effective strategy to improve access.  We present the experience of ten universities in Ethiopia in partnership with the Center for International Reproductive Health Training (CIRHT) at the University of Michigan. The panel will:

  • Describe the state of contraception and CAC training in medical and midwifery schools in Ethiopia
  • Present CIRHT’s pre-service training approach to equip graduates with requisite skills
  • Demonstrate the effectiveness of pre-service training in contraception and CAC in improving knowledge and skills 
  • Present faculty development initiatives to enhance clinical, teaching, and research skills
  • Describe the introduction of simulation-based training in contraception and CAC
  • Discuss the role of quality improvement (QI) initiatives to strengthen training and RH service provision
  • Present the experience of a pioneer model reproductive health clinic founded on the principles of providing comprehensive, women-centered, respectful care

Panel Description

The panel includes technical experts from CIRHT and faculty from universities across Ethiopia who are partnering with CIRHT to improve pre-service training in family planning and CAC, to ultimately improve access and reduce morbidity and mortality from unintended pregnancies.

CIRHT will discuss its approach to introduce structured integration of competency based training in contraception and CAC for medical and midwifery students and OBGYN residents, through academic partnerships.

Bahir Dar University will describe their experience in successfully introducing simulation-based training for medical students to enhance skills teaching in contraception and CAC.

St. Paul’s Hospital Millennium Medical College will describe their experience of setting up a model reproductive health clinic, providing women-centered comprehensive services and a training platform and how this supports its vision to be a Center of Excellence in reproductive health in the region.

Adama General Hospital Medical College will describe their experience implementing QI initiatives and its impact on family planning and CAC services and pre-service training.

Policy Implication

CIRHT’s signature program of supporting formal integration of contraception and CAC training into pre-education has been scaled up to 10 universities in Ethiopia. This program has supported faculty to improve their skills in providing these services and inspired them to teach more effectively. Based on these results, the Ethiopia Federal Ministry of Health is advocating and supporting scale up of this approach to universities and facilities across Ethiopia. The program is now expanding to Rwanda and will continue to expand to additional developing countries.

sessions.sessionDescription:
Adam DICKO (Mali)

Objective: This francophone panel unites 5 West-African youth leaders to showcase how youth leadership literally pays off when programmatic, policy and strategic processes include them unequivocally, from start to finish.

Background: Youth and adolescents make up at least half the population in the 9 Ouagadougou Partnership (OP) countries and this number will increase, as will their unique reproductive health (RH) and family planning (FP) needs.

As countries generate their FP strategies and policies, the unique adolescent and youth sexual and reproductive health and rights (AYSRHR) needs, should be considered. The costed implementation plans (CIPs) are a valuable instrument in this process.

Meaningful youth participation has long been a buzzword, but there are few examples of youth-led approaches resulting in better policies and increased financing. This panel unites five youth leaders active in the West-African youth movement, to showcase how their leadership literally paid because they were involved unequivocally from start to finish and thus able to hold their governments accountable.

Methods: The panelists and moderator, all youth leaders, will provide an insider perspective into an exceptional collaboration between youth, local CSOs, INGOs and the public sector, and underline the urgency to scale-up inclusive AYSRHR program, policy and strategy development. The idea for the successful systematic approach stemmed from a regional Youth ThinkTank led by the OP (panelist 1); was grounded in meticulous analysis and evidence (panelist 2); and co-conceptualized, implemented and monitored by  youth at the national level (panelist 3). Opportunities to adapt and replicate the approach are numerous and urgent (panelist 4) as inaction not an option.

Results: The panelists will present the stand-alone but mutually reinforcing approaches, leading to: increased coordination and transparency between AYSRHR focused actors in the region, accessible data to inform advocacy for AYSRHR; more effective and additional AYSRHR actions and increased funding nationally, an institutionalized role for youth in all processes that concern them and a replicable methodology. Moreover, through innovative skills honing and a youth serving philosophy, youth amplified their voice and agency; essential assets of the future FP leaders the region needs.

Conclusion: The chance to include youth systematically and consistently, in line with a human rights based approach to development, should not be missed if the FP community is serious about improving the health of youth and backing the acceleration phase of the OP which aims to reach 2.2 million additional users of modern contraceptives by 2020.

presentations.title: Supplying for health: How effective distribution of commodities improves family planning outcomes in Rwanda
Increasing use of injectables (DMPA) in community by supporting supply availability via community health workers (CHWs) under Community-Based Provision (CBP) program in Rwanda
Estimating contraceptive prevalence using logistics data for Rwanda
e-LMIS implementation in Rwanda: Ensuring contraceptive security through effective management of logistics data

sessions.sessionDescription:
Rwanda has a mature supply chain system with a strong coordinated procurement and distribution mechanism. The system is integrated and therefore can address all supply chain-related issues, ensuring quality of logistics data through a strong reporting system.

Due in large part to strengthened supply chains and the resulting increase in commodity availability and commodity security, the consumption trend of contraceptives has increased for FP methods since 2011. As availability of long-term implants increased by 324%, from 32,896 units to 139,385 units, demand and distribution of shorter-term methods stayed flat or decreased:

•            38% increase for condoms, from 6.61 million to 9.09 million pieces

•            1% increase for IUDs, from 11,487 to 11,638 units

•            .3% increase for contraceptive pills, from 1,373,589 to 1,377,043 cycles

•            16% decrease for injectables, from 1,534,070 to 1,295,198 vials

•            31% decrease in cycle beads, from 5,388 to 3,703 units

The panel seeks to improve understanding of the:

  • relationship between a well-performing supply chain and increased availability of contraceptives and family planning (FP) uptake
  • impact of increased investments in FP commodities and improved couple years protection (CYP) on reducing unmet need, unplanned pregnancies, and maternal and infant mortality
  • best practices of supply chain system to improve FP access in Rwanda over 15 years

These presentations aim to share Rwanda’s best practices and the contribution of a supply chain management system in improving FP uptake.  Each presentation demonstrates a significant role in attainment of a successful supply chain system in the health sector, from strategy and planning to routine monitoring and data analysis.

The presentations cover four topics: The first presentation focuses on the link between effective distribution of contraceptives and improved FP outcomes. The second describes community distribution of injectable contraceptives and its impact in terms of improved access to contraception. The third explores how logistics data management improves supply chain indicators through the electronic logistics management information system (e-LMIS). The fourth explores advantages of availability of quality logistics data to estimate contraceptive prevalence; this estimate would be used to update decision-makers and inform quick supply chain interventions.
sessions.sessionName: Improving FP Outcomes: Exploring Four Supply Chain Interventions That Have Supported Success in Rwanda

sessions.sessionDescription:
Background:  The London Summit for Family Planning in 2012 secured impressive financial commitments from governments and funders alike to reignite global support for family planning. Yet 2016 marked the second year in a row that global spending for family planning declined among traditional donor governments, who have provided the majority of external aid dollars historically. According to the Kaiser Family Foundation, eighty percent of donor government funding in 2016 came from only three countries: the USA, UK and the Netherlands. At the same time, the landscape for international funding for family planning is shifting as private sources and new partnerships have emerged and are generating important changes in the way global health and family planning operates. What does this mean for family planning? How can our field engage with these emerging private sources and approach new ways of mobilizing funds for family planning? Discussion will center around emerging trends and strategic investments with private funding sources that will include high net worth individuals, family foundations and philanthropic networks.

Objectives:

  • Examine emerging trends and opportunities in a changing funding landscape for global health and outline implications for reproductive, maternal and neonatal health program support
  • Discuss examples of novel funding partnerships to draw lessons from engaging with new actors and mechanisms
  • Articulate different approaches to strategically engage new players in the changing landscape
sessions.sessionName: The Changing Landscape of Philanthropy: Implications for the Development Community

sessions.sessionDescription: Monitoring progress on expanding access to contraception and reducing unmet need for family planning is crucial for stakeholders at multiple perspectives; the global, regional, national, and sub-national levels. This preformed panel aims to inform the family planning community of a shared model used by the United Nations Population Division (UNPD), Track20 (Avenir Health), and University of Massachusetts, to produce family planning indicators at different levels. The audience will learn about the availability of a dataset containing family planning indicators at the global, regional and national level (United Nations Population Division, 2018), the availability of the Family Planning Estimation Tool (FPET) for country monitoring (New & Alkema, 2015), and the use for sub-national monitoring. It will be explained how the estimates and projections are used for the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) and FP2020 monitoring. New developments will be described, including the extension from married-women to all-women and the methods for progress assessment (Cahill et al., 2017). The panel will highlight the extensive efforts undertaken to standardize (where possible) between the initiatives. Whilst there are some small differences between sets of estimates, the key messages are the same and the projects have consistent conclusions about the progress in specific countries.

presentations.title: Making abortion services safer for women in India, policy reflections and way forward
Abortion incidence and service provision in six Indian states: An overview of findings
Role of professional bodies in strengthening women’s access to CAC services
Abortion services in facilities in six states in India

sessionChairs.company: The David and Lucile Packard Foundation

sessions.sessionDescription:
Induced abortion has been legal in India on a broad range of grounds since the Medical Termination of Pregnancy Act was passed in 1971. India, at that time, was among the 15 countries to have a liberal abortion law. However, unsafe abortion is still the third largest cause for maternal deaths in the country. Each day, ten women die as a result of unsafe abortion related reasons (SRS 2002-03). This classification is based on earlier definition of unsafe abortion. There is a change in the landscape for abortion services in India with close to 73% of abortions in India using medical abortion outside the facility. The last available incidence of 6.4 Million abortion in India is from 2002. These estimates did not provide state specific findings or recommendations for strengthening access. A large-scale study of abortion incidence and service provision was conducted by the Guttmacher Institute (New York); International Institute for Population Sciences (Mumbai) and the Population Council (New Delhi).  This study included a representative survey of public and private sector facilities, conducted in six states of India—Assam, Bihar, Gujarat, Madhya Pradesh, Uttar Pradesh and Tamil Nadu—that together comprise about 45% of the country’s population. These states were chosen to represent demographic, economic, social and cultural variation across the country.  The study also captures abortions that take place outside of health facilities, and therefore provides reliable estimates of the overall incidence of abortion. The report for the six state study is in the process of being fianlized and shall be ready for dissemination at the conference.  

Objectives: The objectives of this panel are to: Share findings from a representative sample of health facilities in six states on abortion care provided by public and private health facilities Present the policy recommendations which emerged from the study on strengthening the health system to respond to women’s need for safe abortion services Discuss the challenges in strengthening CAC services in the country 

Expected outcomes: This panel shall highlight the key findings from the six state study highlighting the role of public sector, private sector and out of facility medical abortion for strengthening CAC services in India. The panellists shall also discuss the policy implications for this data and the importance of having data for effective strategies for strengthening CAC interventions at the state level that could be replicated for other states in the country too.
sessions.sessionName: Using Data for Strategizing Women’s Access to Comprehensive Abortion Care in India: Results From a Six State Study on Abortion Incidence in India

sessions.sessionName: Poster Session 3

presentations.title: Beyond the Global Gag Rule: new models for leadership in contraception for the 21st Century

sessions.sessionDescription:
Access to contraception has long been framed within a potentially archaic lens of ‘family planning’, with key conversations about how it supports women and girls’ agency coming second. The SDGs don’t just see contraception as health issue however, but also frame it as central to achieving gender equality. How women and girls decide whether to use contraception matters, as does the impact it has on their lives and what it enables them to do.  With significant unmet need for contraception amongst adolescents, we also need to think about how we make ‘family planning’ fit for purpose, speaking to young people’s needs and potential.

New leadership is leaning forward in support of this agenda, joining with long-term champions. For example, the government of Canada’s Feminist International Assistance Policy puts women and girls at the forefront of development, with sexual and reproductive health and rights an essential enabler on the path towards gender equality.

This panel will provide ICFP with the opportunity to explore, with high-level representation, the pathway to acceleration of universal access to rights-based sexual and reproductive health services.

Objectives

1) To explore the emerging drivers of investments in contraception within the framework of delivering the Sustainable Development Goals. More governments are joining together to recognise the importance of working across development efforts to promote gender equality, applying a gender lens to make programming decisions. Multilaterals such as UNFPA are dedicated to the realisation of the SDGs, and so also bring a broader view of the value of universal access to contraception than only immediate health outcomes. Finally, national governments such as that of Nigeria are building their own business cases for indigenous investment in achieving a demographic dividend for their countries. The panel will explore how these areas can and should drive a different attitude to investment in access to rights-based SRHR services.

2) To explore the challenges to delivering investment in contraception in a world of rising boldness and coordination in the opposition to sexual and reproductive health and rights, a development dialogue in an unstable world that tilts towards prioritising a security and migration agenda, and the implications of the re-imposition of the Mexico City Policy. The panel will showcase data and testimonies from the world’s two largest reproductive health delivery organisations, and from countries (e.g. Nigeria, Uganda and Zimbabwe) where there is enormous opportunity for progress, but also significant risk from the challenges identified in the discussion.

For example the ramifications of changes in funding landscape since 2016 has depleted the funding Marie Stopes International needs to fulfil its FP2020 pledge. While more people than ever are using a method of contraception provided by Marie Stopes International – up 6% in 2017 to 26.9 million – progress has slowed considerably from the 20% increase the previous year.

IPPF has been affected across its whole range of integrated SRHR services including family planning, HIV, sexual and gender based violence, healthcare for men, women and young people. IPPF have estimated that the prevention of 4.8 million unintended pregnancies over three years is a potential reality in the new landscape.

3. To identify key opportunities to driving investment – at national and international level - in delivering increased access to rights-based contraception, building on the world’s commitment to the SDGs.

Presenters:

  • Honourable Marie-Claude Bibeau, Minister of International Development, Canada
  • Prof. Isaac Folorunso Adewole, Minister of Health, Nigeria
  • Dereje Wordofa, UNFPA Deputy Executive Director
  • Dr Alvaro Bermejo, Director General, IPPF
  • Simon Cooke, CEO, Marie Stopes International

Assessing the introduction of generic oral contraceptives to support healthy market development at the global and local level

sessions.sessionDescription:
Overall Panel Objectives: This panel seeks to highlight the important role that generic family planning products can play in the public sector market for reproductive health — showcasing the value that can come from investing in healthy, competitive markets.

Description of the Panel Overall: The global community has focused on ensuring that quality-assured reproductive health products are available at affordable prices. Generic manufacturers are critical to achieve these efforts, mitigate supply risks, and improve overall market health. In addition to price and risk reduction, the introduction of generic manufacturers into the public sector reproductive health market can have an even more important impact in terms of lives improved/saved. The introduction of generic family planning (FP) suppliers into the public donor market can improve market health along all market health dimensions: 1) Global supplier capacity to meet demand; 2) Affordability; 3) Supplier/market stability and sustainability; and 4) Appropriate product choices.

Immediate postpartum provision of long-acting reversible contraceptives (LARC): findings from a single-institution experience
Sharing is caring: How discussions in group-based perinatal care influence attitudes and actions toward postpartum family planning

sessionChairs.company: Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health

sessions.sessionDescription:
Panel Objectives:

  • To disseminate findings from three provider-guided approaches to improving postpartum family planning uptake by increasing women's understanding of contraceptives and facilitating access to services.
  • To share best practices in contraceptive counseling during the perinatal period for dispelling myths and misconceptions related to use of specific methods.

    • Panel Description:

    In areas of low-contraceptive prevalence, rumors and misconceptions about the side effects of family planning can generate concerns about safety and impaired fertility associated with use. Such concerns often prevent women who would like to delay or limit childbearing from using contraceptives. The antenatal and postpartum periods present opportunities for provider engagement to address women's concerns, helping them to develop perspective on the actual risks and benefits of contraceptive use. This preformed panel will highlight three approaches to improving postpartum family planning uptake by addressing women's concerns about contraceptive side effects during antenatal and postpartum visits to support their contraceptive uptake. Panelists will represent perinatal care providers at the facility and community levels, including Group Antenatal Care providers in Nigeria, Roving Auxiliary Nurse Midwives in Nepal, and hospital-based physicians in the United States.

    Panelists will share their first-hand experiences addressing women’s concerns regarding contraceptive side-effects and will share recommendations on how both providers and programs can seize the opportunity of perinatal care provision to improve contraceptive understanding and uptake in the postpartum period.

    Research/Program/Policy implications:

    The programmatic and policy approaches shared in this panel may be adapted for different settings to improve perinatal counseling to address concerns regarding contraceptive side effects, leading to improved uptake and use in the postpartum period. Baltimore-based physicians recently influenced state policy on postpartum LARC use, and this can be shared as a model for policy change in other settings. Success of the group care model may influence antenatal care guidelines, increasing implementation of this model in low and middle-income countries, and presenting an opportunity to make comprehensive discussions on contraceptive side effects a routine part of antenatal care. The Roving Auxiliary Nurse Midwives' work to address concerns among hard to reach women in urban Nepal similarly serves as a model for improving understanding and uptake of contraceptives among vulnerable populations.

presentations.title: Opportunities for CSO to influence the UHC agenda at global, regional and national level through advocacy and accountability
Donors’ role in aligning SRH-related funding to UHC and the value of investing in comprehensive SRH services
Defining the package of services for SRHR in UHC, costing and current data gaps

sessions.sessionDescription:
The panel will provide a roadmap for the sexual and reproductive health (SRH)/family planning (FP) community on technical and policy engagement in the Universal Health Coverage (UHC) agenda, exploring the global and regional normative frameworks, country priority setting process, research and data gaps, and CSO’s critical role. The overall aim of the panel is to contribute to building a movement that ensures that SRH services, including family planning, are included in essential health services packages and covered through national health insurance benefits packages.

The growing momentum and global consensus on UHC has created a unique opportunity to expand access to all health services, but particularly SRH services, including family planning. SRH-related conditions continue to cause a significant portion of the morbidity and mortality in developing countries, much of which is preventable through providing a discrete set of services to women and girls. Many SRH services are potentially sustainable at low cost, making it a feasible proposition when prioritizing the package of services to be included. The broader economic benefits of investing in SRH services are also well-established, further incentivizing the prioritization of women and girls in these efforts. Because of UHC’s strong focus on national ownership and equity, ensuring SRH services are incorporated into this agenda could also help increase domestic ownership (and eventually financing) of these services.

That said, there is no guarantee that SRH services will be included in the operationalization of the UHC agenda. Indeed, while family planning is often listed in countries’ essential health services packages, it is not always included in health benefits packages. Of course, while what specific services are included in any country’s UHC package is decided by countries through a consultative process, this panel will help link the community at ICFP with deep SRH and family planning expertise, with those in the UHC community, to identify ways to advance both agendas in parallel.

With representation from government, donors, civil society and global standard setters, participants will engage in an interactive, solutions-oriented discussion on why and how SRH services, and family planning, can  be incorporated into the UHC agenda. Panelists will also help outline where the opportunities for the SRH/FP community lie to get involved in the UHC agenda and importantly how sectors can work together toward this goal.

Dr. Anders Nordström, Sweden’s Global Health Ambassador, would moderate the discussion, and audience members would be encouraged to ask questions and engage in dialogue.
sessions.sessionName: Sexual and Reproductive Health Services in Universal Health Coverage

presentations.title: Bridging the Gap between Evidence and Action: Exploring Innovative Solutions to address Provider Bias
When “Tried and True” Isn’t: New Monitoring Approaches for Iterative Program Design
Using human centered design to address the needs of rural adolescent mothers in Burkina Faso
Examining the influence of design thinking on project outcomes using a mixed method comparative case-study approach.

sessions.sessionDescription:
Objectives:

1.  Expose and examine the methods and issues in monitoring and evaluating (M&E) projects using human-centered design principles and methods;

2.  Explore the relevance of traditional Institutional Review Boards in assessing protocol for iterative methods and practices; and

3.  Discuss how public health evaluation and research systems will need to adapt (or not) to support methods that demonstrate potential in unpacking and addressing demand-side barriers.

Description:

In recent years, there has been an increasing interest within global health in private sector methodologies used to unpack consumer needs, desires, and behaviors to design customized products, services, and experiences for customers. Much of this impetus has come from global concern that ‘more of the same’ is being done, while aiming for better results. Implementing organizations are using design thinking to generate insights around why specific populations choose to use family planning methods (or not). Discovered insights are used to build and test ‘prototypes’ through user testing, rapid experimentation, and refinement through iteration and feedback. Prototypes demonstrating promising results are then evaluated more rigorously.

These non-traditional disciplines that design to the local context are being implemented within programs and health systems generally governed by conventional public health standards prioritizing scale, reach, impact, and global best practice. This ‘context-scale tension’ spills over into the M&E of programs that engage these methods. Implementing partners have had to rapidly innovate and advance ways to collect, document, monitor, and evaluate these methods and interventions to address M&E best practice questions. Join us in an experiential debate based on the solutions, lessons, and results emerging from multi-country projects. Our panelists will share their rationales, results, and lessons learned along one of two “debate-axes” – projects using design principles must focus their evaluation on results produced by the solutions; and projects using design principles must not be subject to ethical reviews. Each taking a “pro” or “anti” stance while debating based on their implementation experience. Audiences will be engaged through “voting with their feet” on each topic and will be asked to share their own experiences within each issue. Our aim is to expose, explore, and examine the issues, solutions, and trade-offs recognizing the potential of newer methods to moving the needle in enabling 120 million more women and girls to use contraceptives by 2020.

Research/program/policy implications:

1. Reference community of practice

2. Learning agenda development

3. Link to iterative programming and CLA

4. Developing and advancing new standards that are more aligned with these methods·

sessionChairs.company: Institute for Reproductive Health Georgetown University

sessions.sessionDescription:
Objectives:

  • Describe approaches to sensitizing Muslim and Christian religious leaders in family planning
  • Learn how religious leaders respond to and utilize new family planning information
  • Share recommendations and key considerations for replication

Description: More than 200 million women in the developing world want to avoid pregnancy but currently are not using family planning (FP). At the London Summit in 2012, policy makers called for initiatives to expand access to FP. Achieving these goals requires broad mobilization of resources and engagement by all sectors, including religious leaders to reach beyond the traditional health system and expand FP access. Primary reasons for non-use of FP are real or perceived side effects of methods, inaccurate perceptions of pregnancy risk, and social opposition. Preferences for family size and use of FP are reinforced through social norms and community structures, including religion. While many see religion as perpetuating harmful social norms, it can also be part of the solution. Faith communities shape individual and collective values such as human dignity, forgiveness, and respect and care for people as image-bearers of God. These values affect relationships from the most intimate to the most distant. Religious leaders and individual congregations at the grassroots level are important gatekeepers in disseminating reproductive health messages and influencing positive behavior change within communities

Implications: Many religious leaders are confronted with the same myths and misconceptions about FP as their followers. By equipping them with accurate and appropriate information, they can begin to shift norms that hinder FP access. Working with religious leaders “where they are”, and engaging with them on issues that expand their ability to reach the communities they serve in ways that are consistent with their underlying values (e.g., the importance of the family as a social unit, the nurturing role of parents, respect between husbands and wives, birth spacing) can open up new avenues for dialog and remove barriers to FP access. Religious leaders have the power to increase significantly the demand for and use of health services, reduce stigma and myths related to FP, and increase male engagement. Therefore, it is important to share challenges and lessons learned from these experiences across a variety of contexts.

sessions.sessionName: Poster Session 4

sessions.sessionDescription:
More than half of the world’s population is under the age of 25. Youth are passionate, energetic, and powerful, and will inherit the world, including the challenges that come with it. Issues that affect youth – education, the prevention of teenage pregnancy, gender equity and employment, to name a few – deserve the attention of leaders, policy-makers, researchers, and advocates of all ages. 

This youth plenary session will focus on diversity in FP. When we talk about diversity, we talk about unity. Unity among us all to work together and to work with groups that we don’t normally work with to further our efforts. The plenary which will be non-traditional and include monologues and interactive elements will be focused on diversity in family planning and highlight the lived realities of youth from all over the world and programs that have successfully integrated diversity around family planning. Monologues will be interspersed with visuals focused on emphasizing the data which back-up the stories or highlight the solutions in different regions.

presentations.title: How contraceptive availability affects contraceptive use: a cluster-level panel analysis

authors.company: Bloomberg School of Public Health, Johns Hopkins University

sessions.sessionDescription:
Over the past five years, new facility survey data have come available that enable the tracking of contraceptive commodity availability over time and across multiple countries, providing trends data on method availability and service quality.  When linked with population-based surveys, we gain further insights on how the availability affects contraceptive use. This session considers advances that have been made across two monitoring and evaluation survey programs:  UNFPA Supplies Facility Surveys, a facility-based survey conducted in over 30 countries since 2013; and Performance Monitoring and Accountability 2020 (PMA2020), linked household and service delivery point surveys conducted in 11 countries across 47 rounds since 2013.  Both surveys have improved availability of facility-level data in resource-poor settings, which has been lacking compared to population-based data.  They encompass data across multiple countries in Africa, where in many instances there has been dramatic recent changes in contraceptive use.  UNFPA Supplies Facility Surveys includes client exit interviews providing data on experiential quality, whereas PMA2020 survey design allows measuring population’s access methods and its impact on use.  Understanding the survey methodologies and recent trend data will improve data use by various stakeholders and facilitate identification of data and research gap in supply, access, quality, and use.  In addition, country experience in conducting the two surveys and utilizing the data will provide further comparison and contrast of the methods and opportunity and challenges in using the data. The final panelist will present impact of current and past availability of a method on use of the method at the community level, using the linked household and facility surveys in PMA2020.    

The session objectives are to: 

(1) provide an overview of new survey data that enable analyses of contraceptive supply dynamics and their relationship to use,

(2) demonstrate how these data can be used to: monitor trends in contraceptive method availability, access, and quality; and evaluate the impact of access to methods on contraceptive use over time, and

(3) compare and contrast two survey programs in Ethiopia.

Implications for policies, programs, research:  This session will present data and analyses that reveal important supply-access-quality-use dynamics that can inform policies and programs in the countries of focus – and can be adapted in other countries for the benefit of policy leaders and program managers.  It will also provide insights into new facility survey methodologies that can inform other survey research programs.

sessionChairs.company: RAISE Initiative, Heilbrunn Department of Population and Family Health, Mailman School of Public Health, Columbia University

sessions.sessionDescription:
Panel objectives

Evidence showing successful implementation of contraceptive services in humanitarian settings has been limited.  The purpose of this panel is to demonstrate the successful implementation of contraceptive programs, including increasing utilization of long-acting and permanent methods (LAPM), in a variety of humanitarian settings and share strategies that contributed to this success.

Description:

The ten countries with the highest maternal mortality ratios in the world are affected by, or emerging from, war; these countries are also characterized by low contraceptive prevalence. Despite the inclusion of sexual and reproductive (SRH) services in the minimum standards of health care in humanitarian settings, access to SRH services is often compromised in war.  Although evidence that demand for contraception exists in humanitarian settings, contraceptive services are rarely provided.  Although a broad range of methods is an essential component of good contraceptive programming, LAPM are rarely provided in humanitarian settings.

CARE, International Rescue Committee (IRC) and Save the Children, in collaboration with the RAISE Initiative, support the provision of contraceptive services, including LAPM, in public-sector health facilities in humanitarian settings across Africa and Asia. Support includes competency-based training and supportive supervision of providers, ensuring supply of contraceptive methods and supplies and community mobilization activities.

Presenters will demonstrate that the provision of good quality contraceptive services, including LARC, is feasible in humanitarian settings, and that women will use them by sharing the results of contraceptive prevalence surveys in program areas in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (23% modern method prevalence, 11% LAPM prevalence) and method mix program data from multiple countries showing over 50% use of LAPM.  Presenters will then share programmatic strategies used achieve these successful results including the integration of post-partum IUDs and ongoing clinical coaching of providers.

Research/program/policy implications

Making good quality contraceptive services available is challenging and requires sustained effort, funding and program adjustments. These programs demonstrate their success in providing services in humanitarian settings.  Given true choice, when a range of methods was routinely available, women were able to choose the method that best served their needs, increasingly LARCs. The results contribute to the limited evidence on contraception in humanitarian settings, and demonstrate that even in remote and unstable settings, when good quality contraceptive services, with a choice of short-acting, long-acting and permanent methods, are in place, women will exercise their right to reproductive choice.

sessions.sessionDescription:
Objectives: Through a moderated discussion led by the International Union for the Scientific Study of Population (IUSSP) with four leading experts in urban fertility and family planning (FP) issues, and interaction with the audience, this panel will address the pressing issues of FP, fertility and welfare in urban sub-Saharan Africa and South Asia. 

Description: World population will grow by 2.4 billion between 2015 and 2050, an increase of close to one-third. Three-fourths of this increase will occur in sub-Saharan Africa and South Asia, regions that account for over 80% of the world population living in absolute poverty.  Future population growth will occur almost entirely in urban areas, and the world urban population is projected to increase by two-thirds by 2050. While many new arrivals in the informal neighborhoods of cities are rural-urban migrants, much of this growth will be due to the larger number of births than deaths among urban residents. Sub-Saharan Africa and South Asia exhibit the highest rates of urban population growth, currently estimated at 3.8% per year for sub-Saharan Africa (doubling every 18 years), and 2.4% per year for South Asia (doubling every 29 years).

Cities are more unequal than rural areas. Most are struggling to keep pace with rapid population growth in terms of vital infrastructure. Roughly one in three urban residents in Asia and Africa lives in slums with limited access to basic services, including health and FP services, sanitation, clean water and education. While urban fertility has fallen in recent years, unmet need for modern contraception and unwanted fertility are high, and the rapid growth in the number of adolescents and other disadvantaged subgroups living in cities translates into enormous needs for targeted sexual and reproductive health services.

Implications: Universal access to high quality FP services should be an integral part of efforts aimed at building sustainable cities and economic prosperity for all, with implications for gender equity, women’s economic empowerment and the demographic dividend. Reducing unwanted fertility also benefits maternal health and poverty alleviation, and the slower pace of urban growth will facilitate the achievement of other goals. However, to date, policy discussions on urban development and health, as well as on “sustainable cities” (SDG 11), generally neglect the important role of FP as an influence on various dimensions of urban life.  Discussion will focus on the most vulnerable with limited access to FP/RH services: adolescents, recent migrants, and residents of urban slums.
