Beginning with the End in Mind: Multiple Meanings for Contraceptive Research and Development

sessions.sessionDescription:
There are numerous and various forms of effective, and safe contraception on the market today, and yet millions of women and men, mainly in low-and middle-income countries (LMICs), still have an unmet need for family planning. Accessibility of contraception methods does not only depend on their availability and affordability, but also, importantly, on their suitability for the individual user and their circumstances. For example, products might have to be self-administrable without the help of health workers. In some contexts, tools have to be discreet so they cannot require a daily routine, in other contexts, multipurpose tools are needed that can at the same time prevent disease and pregnancy. New and improved tools are thus critically needed to fill these gaps and enable women and men worldwide to access voluntary, quality contraception that suits their needs.

Contraceptive R&D, when targeted to vulnerable populations in LMICs who currently have an unmet need for family planning, does not provide strong market incentives for the private sector to invest. Alternative innovation models and public R&D funding are thus urgently needed to allow for contraceptive product innovations to target underserved populations. This will ensure that the immense health and economic benefits that contraceptives can bring, will leave no one behind, as promised by the 2030 Agenda.

This panel therefore brings together four organisations who “innovate to meet the need”, moderated by an organisation that advocates for public health R&D funding to focus on neglected societal challenges. 

Objectives of the panel:

  • Increase the audience’s knowledge of latest developments in contraceptive innovation and cutting edge tools
  • Discuss how such innovative tools could expand the acceptability, and thus voluntary use of contraception
  • Discuss gaps in the current R&D efforts in particular the funding need for  the cost-effectiveness and other benefits of the availability of suitable family planning methods for sustainable development

Research-/program- and policy- implications:

The research presented here will answer questions about the safety, appropriateness and effectiveness of different new products that are finding their way into SRH programmes

sessions.sessionDescription:
Objectives:

- Present recent normative change processes in family planning promoted by faith actors

- Investigate strategies applied and lessons learnt by faith actors

- Identify main drivers of normative change in family planning within faith actors

- Engage participants in reflection on future steps to promote change in family planning norms through faith organisations

Description:

The World Bank suggests that ‘fertility transitions may be better viewed as a norm-driven process than as the aggregate outcome of autonomous decisions’ (2015 World Development Report). Social norms are people’s shared expectations and beliefs on how people should behave (ODI 2015). In particular, religious beliefs often affect individuals’ behaviours which impact health, including age at marriage, family structure and roles and preventive health practices like strategies couples use to achieve their preferred family size. Furthermore, misinterpretation of religious teachings fosters harmful practices including child marriage and female genital mutilation.

As “norm entrepreneurs” faith actors are well-suited to leading the change of social norms in family planning. Passionate individuals, who are well connected or highly central to a faith organization, or who have high status can play a key role in catalysing normative change in family planning. In this panel, four norm entrepreneurs will describe processes of normative change they are promoting. They will describe main milestones, lessons and results and provide an outlook on future developments.

Recent developments within the Anglican Church comprise the Council of African Provinces of Africa’s resolution to promote family planning coupled with practical actions in universities and dioceses. Supreme Council of Kenya Muslims has changed its interpretation of child spacing in Islam and has renewed its theological and scholarly ties with Al Azhar University-Cairo. Using its Faith for Life model, Christian Aid has enabled local faith groups to embrace maternal and child health and family planning in Isiolo and Narok counties, Kenya. In turn, Tearfund and Église du Christ au Congo champion positive masculinities, denounce intimate partner violence and promote family planning with institutionalization in mind.

Implications:

These are powerful examples promoting normative change in family planning from within faith organizations. Faith to Action Network encourages and supports such organizational transformations at all levels so that these interventions are applied widely. Family planning needs to be integrated into theology and pastoral care, institutional policies and practice, faith-run schools, universities and health facilities. Exposure to these new ideas and practices on family planning need to be discussed through formal and informal channels, including through places of worship and media.

sessions.sessionDescription: To achieve the collective goal of enabling 120 million more women and girls to use contraception by 2020, we need to start with young people. While many of the 50 countries that have made commitments to advance the goals of FP2020 included commitments to adolescents and youth, there has been less progress in advancing these adolescent- and youth-focused goals to improve family planning services and contraception access. Often, adolescents and youth, especially young women, have been marginalized in moving the FP agenda forward. PAI’s YOUAccess fund supports youth-led organizations to advance FP policies, increase budget allocations for youth friendly health services, and strengthen organizational capacity. As part of YOUAccess, PAI has built partnerships with a variety of youth-led organizations, many of which led by empowered young women. This panel aims to highlight the work of three YOUAccess partners – all empowered young women. Yordanos Wolde from Talent Youth Association in Ethiopia is a member of the Ethiopian Youth Council for Higher Opportunities (ECHO), which is designed to develop young leaders in the areas of family planning, sexual reproductive health and global HIV and AIDS. She works with officials within the Ethiopian government to implement youth friendly health policies, ensuring that there is meaningful youth engagement. Vanessa Anyoti has been working with YWCA in Tanzania for several years. With support from her organization, she has become a effective advocate for youth SRHR. Most recently, she has worked with district level stakeholders to address gender inequality in two districts of Tanzania. Natasha Salifyanji Kaoma co-founded Copper Rose Zambia when she saw the lack of sanitary pads in her school. She has since become an advocate for adolescent and youth SRHR. Working at the community level, Natasha aims inform community members of the latest information on SRHR and encourage them to use their collective voice to change negative perceptions about youth SRHR. These three impressive young women are committed to improving SRHR outcomes for young people. They will share their successes and challenges in building their careers champions of SRHR as well as how to better support other young women to be the next generation of change-makers.

presentations.title: Application of FP Demand Analysis and Segmentation as an SBC Innovation
Segmentation using a qualitative, longitudinal lens:  Research from Benin on social influence and women’s and men’s pathways to modern family planning

authors.company: Institute for Reproductive Health, Georgetown University

sessionChairs.company: Institute for Reproductive Health, Georgetown University

sessions.sessionDescription: As efforts to achieve Family Planning 2020 and the Sustainable Development Goals gain momentum, new research and program paradigms could provide useful approaches for women and men to meet their FP needs, and for policy and program implementers to address lagging FP uptake and growing unmet need in West Africa and elsewhere. Implementers, researchers, and policymakers are paying renewed attention to market segmentation to improve FP uptake (Patsika et al. 2009; USAID 2011; Winfrey 2013; Rimal et al. 2009; Camber Collective 2015).  Market segmentation, or audience segmentation, has a long history in commercial marketing to guide investments in product promotional activities (Rimal and Adkins 2003; Slater 1996) and first entered the public health field in the 1970s (Kotler 1972) and gained momentum in the 1990s (Zimmerman et al. 1994; Broom and Dozier 1990).  Most public health segmentation has used demographic, socio-economic, and/or psychographic characteristics, derived from cross-sectional survey designs.  These derived typologies of FP users, though, have not improved program outcomes as they have not sufficiently predicted behavior (Rimal and Adkins 2003; Patsika et al. 2009; Camber Collective 2015).  This panel focuses on several recent FP market segmentation efforts aiming to address such deficiencies – exploring a range of quantitative and qualitative approaches guided by different theoretical lenses to segment program audiences to improve family planning method uptake. The Camber Collective’s (2017) survey work in Niger employs multidimensional segments incorporating behavioral and attitudinal factors, and offers promising segmentation approaches to improve understanding of potential FP users, and identify the most promising opportunities for program intervention.  In Benin, Georgetown University’s Institute for Reproductive Health’s used a longitudinal cohort study (2015.2016) to investigate qualitatively the processes and mechanisms involved in FP behavior change among women and men, applying a social network lens to analyze social influences on FP use operating within and between social-ecological levels.  Our findings question some traditional ideas about FP programming, which may target women and men solely based upon demographic or geographic factors.  The two presentations set the stage for interactive work with the audience around how to practically integrate segmentation approaches into FP promotion and services, and more conceptually, how to shift prevalent paradigms to use new strategies for reaching those most likely to change or to work more precisely with socio-normative drivers of FP update will close the session.

Uganda GFF Civil Society Engagement Strategy: Results of joint advocacy efforts

Nigeria GFF Performance Scorecard for Accountability

sessionChairs.company: Johns Hopkins Center for Communication Programs

sessions.sessionDescription:
The Global Financing Facility in support of Every Woman Every Child (GFF) is mobilizing resources to close the funding gap to meet the Sustainable Development Goals, including achieving universal access to sexual and reproductive health-care and family planning.  It is also a key potential source of financing in support of the global partnership Family Planning 2020. 

Civil society plays a key role advocating for prioritization of evidence-based family planning and reproductive health programs in country plans for GFF, and follow-up accountability.  But what advocacy and accountability approaches and tools have been most effective in leveraging GFF funds for family planning and reproductive health?  Who are the most important advocacy targets in GFF countries, and which champions can be mobilized to reach these decision-makers?  How can civil society advocates for family planning effectively position themselves in coalition with partners across the continuum of care, and yield results in family planning?  How does global advocacy bolster country-level advocacy and accountability? 

This panel offers a unique insider perspective on coordinated GFF advocacy interventions that span across and within countries.  The panel will start by: (1) Demonstrating the ways that a global civil society coalition coordinated research and advocacy interventions to impact a favorable policy environment for GFF engagement at the country level.  The rest of the panel will show how the resulting policy framework for CSO engagement in GFF processes was used to facilitate effective advocacy and accountability at country level.  Specifically, we will: (2) Make evident the powerful advocacy strategies that civil society has used to leverage GFF funds for family planning; and (2) Share the most effective accountability tools and approaches for monitoring GFF investments during implementation. 

The information conveyed by the panelists is directly relevant for champions of family planning in a growing number of GFF countries.  The facility is currently active in 26 countries including Rwanda, and aims to expand to a total of 50 countries with a new wave of funding in the next three years.  All of these countries have unmet needs for family planning that could be impacted by increased levels of funding and prioritization of high impact interventions.  Furthermore, the GFF is celebrated as a standard-bearer for new models of innovative financing.  The interventions and approaches described in this panel have potential for application in other funding mechanisms and global processes including UHC 2030.
sessions.sessionName: Local-Global GFF Advocacy & Accountability for Family Planning: Interventions that Work

presentations.title: Rapid, Substantial, Equitable: A deep dive into gains in implant use in Sub-Saharan Africa
Ten Million Women and Counting: How Marie Stopes International has supported Africa’s scale-up of implants
Impressive Gains in Implant Uptake: Enabling factors and future prospects
Insights from Implant Users, and the Future of Consumer-focused Implant Services

sessions.sessionDescription:
Panel Objective: To highlight the marked uptake of contraceptive implants occurring in much of sub-Saharan Africa (SSA) among almost all sociodemographic categories. At the end of the session the audience will know how, where, and to what extent implants have broadened method choice, become highly popular, and been the main contributor to FP2020 gains achieved by at least 11 SSA countries.

Panel Description: The panel consists of interlinked presentations describing: 1) Key findings in our analyses of multiple PMA2020 and DHS surveys from 12 countries comprising 61% of sub-Saharan Africa’s population (these  findings highlight rapid, ongoing increases in implant use through March 2018 and will be continually updated through October 2018); 2) Quantitative and qualitative findings from implant service provision by Marie Stopes International and Population Services International in 16 SSA countries; 3) Public sector experience with task-shifting of implant provision to Community Health Extension Workers (CHEWs) in Ethiopia (presented by panel moderator); and, 4) Organizational perspectives from the Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation, a primary driver of our community’s efforts to broaden FP access and choice. We will show how this most effective of all methods, which only had 1.1% prevalence of use in SSA as recently as 2011, has become the 1st or 2nd most widely-used method in 10 African countries, with gains in implant use alone exceeding combined gains in injectables, pill and IUD use. In countries as diverse as Burkina Faso and Ethiopia, Congo Democratic Republic and Ghana, Kenya and Senegal, implants now account for 1/4 to ½ of all modern method use. Substantially increased uptake has occurred among sexually-active unmarried women as well as married women, women of low and high parity, and among all ages, education levels, and wealth quintiles. Ample time will be devoted to audience dialogue regarding research, program, and policy aspects of this yet-unfolding, nearly-unprecedented FP success story.

Policy and Program Implications: Key policy and program factors addressed include marked price reductions, much-increased commodity supply, greater government commitment to FP, broadened WHO eligibility guidance, and wider adoption of high-impact service delivery approaches that increase access and better reach underserved populations. With continued program commitment and donor support, these trends in implant uptake are very likely to continue the next few years. This implies continuing need for the international FP community to maintain its focus on rights-based programming, ensuring reliable access to implant removal as well as insertion services, and addressing issues of financing and sustainability.
sessions.sessionName: The Blossoming of Implant Use in Africa: How It Happened and What Lies Ahead

sessions.sessionDescription:
Objectives

This session aims to increase understanding and awareness of the reproductive desires of married adolescents and young women, as well as their ability to actualize those desires. Highlighting recent research from diverse settings in Africa and South Asia, the panelists will address not only these intentions, but also some of the barriers that married adolescents and young women face to accessing reproductive health services, including specific family planning methods, in line with their needs.

Description

While there is an increasing evidence base both on interventions that aim to prevent child marriage and to expand access by adolescents to sexual and reproductive health information and services, little is known about either the reproductive intentions of married adolescents and young people or their ability to act on those intentions. Bringing together new evidence from a longitudinal study in India (Young Lives) and from three implementing organizations working in Bangladesh, Niger, Pakistan, Tanzania, Burkina Faso, Zambia, and India (Population Council, CARE and Pathfinder), this session will advance our global understanding of the reproductive desires and needs of adolescents and young women, the barriers they face in accessing the information and services that can help them to achieve those desires, and potential solutions to overcming those barriers.   

Research/Program/Policy Implications

The latest data from UNICEF indicate that there are more than 650 million women alive today who were married as children, and that roughly 12 million more girls continue to marry before the age of 18 each year.[1] Girls who marry as children are more likely to be poor, out of school, and have less decision-making power than women who marry over the age of 18. They also tend to have higher fertility and maternal mortality rates, earlier age at first birth, and lower use of contraception later in life as compared to women who marry after 18.[2] Even as organizations and governments work to eliminate child marriage, it is thus critical for the FP/SRHR community to understand the reproductive intentions of married girls and young women, as well as the barriers they face in achieving them, so that interventions can be designed to most effectively meet their needs.  

 

[1] https://data.unicef.org/topic/child-protection/child-marriage/#

[2] Wodon, Q., C. Male, A. Nayihouba, A. Onagoruwa, A. Savadogo, A. Yedan, J. Edmeades, A. Kes, N. John, L. Murithi, M. Steinhaus and S. Petroni (2017). Economic Impacts of Child Marriage: Global Synthesis Report, Washington, DC: The World Bank and International Center for Research on Women.

sessions.sessionDescription:
Objectives:

  • Share results from a landscaping report on the relationship between intimate partner violence (IPV) and family planning (FP)
  • Describe approaches and promising practices for integrated interventions addressing IPV and FP
  • Share recommendations for advancing work on integrated IPV-FP interventions

Description: Research shows that IPV is a key barrier to meeting the FP intentions of women and men. A relationship between IPV and FP has been documented, but we know little of the underlying mechanisms driving this relationship, and as a result, effective approaches for integrated response[1]. Patriarchal notions of the roles of males and females and male control over women influence decisions for FP and acceptability and perpetration of IPV. As part of a landscaping to synthesize evidence on the relationship between IPV and FP, a variety of integrated IPV-FP intervention approaches were identified and categorized, ranging from social and behavior change, edutainment, economic empowerment, and service delivery. This panel will highlight several examples of promising approaches to integrated programming.   

Research/Program/Policy Implications: Globally, groundbreaking research and programming related to IPV and FP are taking place. A better understanding of the mechanisms and processes that successfully address IPV, FP and the linkages between the two is critical to improve the lives of women and their families globally. Integrated IPV-FP programming offers an opportunity to achieve wider improvements in women’s sexual and reproductive health in addition to preventing violence in the home.

[1] Gilles, K. (2015). Intimate Partner Violence and Family Planning: Opportunities for Action. Population Reference Bureau. Washington, DC.

presentations.title: Updates on the Family Planning Training Resource Package
Adaptation of the TRP for Pre-Service Education of Nurses and Midwives in Uganda
Contraceptive Method Mix, a Quality Indicator
Training Resource Package: Documentation of Experiences on Use in the Field

sessions.sessionDescription:
In order to provide high-quality services, effective family planning (FP) programs require health workers who have up-to-date knowledge and skills in addition to positive attitudes. However, many developing countries have limited awareness and access to evidence-based training materials to develop knowledge and skills among FP health workers. The Training Resource Package for Family Planning (TRP) is an evidence-based training tool to be used alongside other current materials such as the Medical Eligibility Criteria for Contraceptive Use, 2015 and the Global Family Planning Handbook. The TRP contains curriculum, resources, and tools for a program to implement and evaluate FP training.  It provides resources for trainers, supervisors, and program managers. USAID, in partnership with the World Health Organization (WHO), the United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA), and other stakeholders has supported the development and rollout of the TRP. The TRP has been implemented in several countries. In Afghanistan, the use of just one TRP module assisted in the updating of the national FP guidelines, in developing FP curricula for pre-service and in-service training, in adapting materials to the country’s context, and in conducting competency-based training. In many instances, the process involved the adaptation of materials to align with national FP service delivery and training policies/guidelines, country-specific training curricula, and translations into local languages. The use of TRP materials may involve all the modules or just a subset depending on needs.

Panelists will share their experiences in the adaptation of the TRP for in-service and pre-service education in Tanzania, Uganda, and Afghanistan. The presentation will include results from a global review of implementation of the TRP. Specifically, the presentations will share the methodology and process of adaptation for pre-service education for nurses and midwives in Uganda and the adaptation of a singular TRP module for in-service training of FP providers in Afghanistan. Further, the presentations will share the results of an assessment on the perspectives of stakeholders during the dissemination and promotion of the TRP. The presentation will include the frequency and timeliness of updates of the TRP materials to ensure the materials reflect new guidance, such as Medical Eligibility Criteria, and the process for updating TRP materials.

Presentations will the various ways that the TRP has been adapted and used. Lessons learned will strengthen the promotion of the TRP and enhance its the usability in more countries and among different training contexts.

sessions.sessionDescription:
Objectives: The objective of this panel is to share evidence on how power differentials within couples and decision-making processes influence contraceptive use.

Description: There is increased interest in understanding how couple dynamics, especially women’s level of influence in the decision-making process, relate to increased contraceptive use, choice, and self-efficacy to fulfill one’s reproductive goals. In many low and middle-income countries, men often have major influence in important decisions in the family, including reproduction, family size and contraceptive use.  Women’s ability to control her fertility can strongly be affected by social constructs of gender role, expectations and gender inequalities.

In this panel, we bring you evidence from four countries—Niger, the DRC, Nigeria and India. The presentation from Niger focuses on a novel method of measuring the relative influence of decision-making related to family planning among married adolescent girls. Qualitative data from the DRC dives deeper into the various factors that impact post-partum family planning uptake, noting how those factors differentially influence married young women versus unmarried young women’s uptake. Data from Nigeria offers a nuanced measurement of how couples make decisions, while the data from India shares that greater decision-making power is associated with ever use of contraceptive.

Three of the four projects fall under the Women and Girls at the Center of Development (WGCD) investment by the Gates Foundation.

Research/program/policy implications: Ensuring women’s voice, choice and power in the decision-making process will support their rights to meet their own reproductive goals, a key objective of FP2020. Deeply embedded social norms related to gender roles lead to unmet need for family planning. By understanding how decision-making power is associated with contraceptive use, implementers can tailor programming to promote joint decision-making related to the negotiation of fertility intentions and family planning use, especially in contexts were unequal gender norms limit girls’ agency to negotiate their reproductive desires. Programming should be designed strategically to recognize and promote the importance of couple communication and men’s roles and influence about decisions around family size and the use of family planning. Findings can inform the design of gender-synchronized interventions which improve couple decision-making and increase male support for family planning, when and where it makes sense to do so.

sessions.sessionDescription:
Objectives

To share country experiences of scaling up and sustaining sexuality education by building community support and dealing effectively with resistance in diverse contexts.

Description

Despite recognition of the need for sexuality education and growing acceptance that sexuality education is a right; availability of evidence of effectiveness and cost effectiveness; availability of tools to advocate, plan, monitor, and evaluate programs; and inclusion of sexuality education in regional/national commitments and plans of action, progress at implementation of sexuality education in high, middle and low income countries alike has been slow.

Across settings, a common challenge is moving from small-scale projects or weakly designed and executed programs with poor quality and limited coverage to large-scale, well-designed and well-conducted programs coordinated by Ministries of Education and included in national school education policies and frameworks. This transition faces barriers at multiple levels related to: comfort, commitment, capacity, cash, and accountability. Additionally, programs face the challenge of preventing paralysis due to backlash during implementation and reviving progress if they become stalled by resistance.

Program/policy implications

A small number of countries, such as Pakistan, India, Nigeria, and Argentina, have scaled-up and sustained sexuality education, and can provide insights into effective strategies and investments. These recommendations include placing sexuality education on the national agenda, planning the scale-up of sexuality education from the start, managing the scale-up of sexuality education effectively and efficiently, building support while anticipating and addressing opposition, promoting and safeguarding sustainability, and understanding potential barriers at different levels.

presentations.title: Do the three questions of the MII sufficiently capture process quality? Insights from a longitudinal study of reversible contraceptive users in India
Comparing method information index data from household surveys with direct observations in health facility surveys in Nepal and Tanzania
Applying the Method Information Index (MII) to performance-based financing platforms to improve quality of care

sessions.sessionDescription:
The Method Information Index (MII) is calculated from contraceptive users' responses to questions regarding counseling content: whether they were informed about other methods, method-specific side effects, and what to do if they experienced side effects. MII is increasingly reported in facility and household surveys and used to track country performance in the global FP2020 initiative, but little is known about its properties and its predictive capability in contraceptive outcomes. 

This panel presents evidence on the integrity of the index with inclusion of additional items, whether MII is predictive of contraceptive discontinuation, what is means to ask MII at facility exit versus households, and the policy and programmatic implications of linking MII to financial incentives in performance-based financing programs. 

By end of the panel, participants will be able:

  • to identify the key items in the MII and supplemental dimensions
  • to describe the differences in interpretation of quality when using MII data from different sources 
  • to examine whether the MII score is related to contraceptive outcomes, specifically discontinuation
  • to isolate the policy and programmatic challenges and opportunities in linking MII to performance incentives in RBF programs 

This panel addresses several major research priorities, including: 1) probing the reliability and construct validity of the index; 2) testing the predictive capabilities of MII with respect to users’ contraceptive outcomes; and 3) presenting results from a test that expands the explanatory power of the index. Findings indicate that data collected from exit interviews are not comparable to those collected from retrospective population surveys. However, the collection of MII data via exit interviews is efficient, free from recall bias, and predictive of contraceptive discontinuation. The reason for differences between client provided and directly observed information on the provider-client interaction and the aspects of facility quality for which MII can serve as a proxy need to be further understood as programs consider methods of data collection. 

There are several policy implications as well. MII is already a key indicator in the global FP2020 Track20 initiative, and routinely collected in DHS surveys. It has the potential to inform program management and resource allocations. In results-based financing (RBF) programs and FP strategic purchasing initiatives, linking MII to financial rewards may have unintended consequences of affecting how quality is reported. The MII has the possibility of being a universal indicator of FP quality, but differences between national and facility level assessments pose challenges for the FP2020 initiative.

presentations.title: Le rôle de l’Organisation Ouest Africaine de la Santé dans la promotion de la délégation des tâches de PF en Afrique de l’Ouest
La délégation des tâches est une condition sine qua none pour l’atteinte des objectifs du Partenariat de Ouagadougou en 2020
La délégation des tâches fait sa marque au Burkina Faso
La délégation des tâches pour la planification familiale en Côte d’Ivoire : de la politique en action

sessions.sessionDescription:
Panel Objectives: Dans les nombreuses régions du monde la délégation des tâches dans la prestation de services de planification familiale (PF) est devenue routinière. Pendant plusieurs années, il n’est resté que l’Afrique de l’Ouest francophone (AOF) à adopter une stratégie de délégation des tâches. Depuis longtemps cette région a été distinguée par une fertilité haute, une médicalisation forte de la PF et une résistance culturelle forte à la contraception moderne. Cette région a aussi des déficits remarquables de ressources humaines de la santé. L’objectif principal de cette discussion est de suivre le voyage continu en AOF de la promesse à la politique, à la pratique et à la prévalence (TPC) en ce qui concerne la délégation des tâches aux prestataires de première ligne (et dans certains cas aux femmes elles-mêmes).

Description : Dans 4 présentations interdépendantes des principaux acteurs en AOF représentant deux points de vue régionaux et deux points de vue nationaux. Les panélistes présenteront la logique, les actions politiques, les facteurs de mise en œuvre, et les financements nécessaires pourque la délégation des tâches de PF devienne une réalité dans la région. Cela inclut la fourniture des implants par les agents de première ligne (les accoucheuses brevetées/auxiliaires/aides-soignants) ; la fourniture des produits injectables par les agents de santé communautaires ; et la fourniture à domicile et l’auto-injection de Sayana Press. La résolution récente de l’Assemblée des Ministres de la Santé de la Communauté Economique des Etats de l’Afrique de l’Ouest (CEDEAO) sur la délégation des tâches de PF aux cadres de niveau le plus bas du système de santé devrait contribuer à servir plus de femmes et l’atteinte des objectifs FP2020 mais il reste à voir son impact réel.

Research/policy/program implications : Il y a plusieurs questions clés qui restent. Quels sont les efforts supplémentaires (programmes/plaidoyer) nécessaires pour aller à l’échelle dans la délégation des tâches aux agents de santé de première ligne et aux ASC ? De quelle importance a été la résolution de la CEDEAO en supprimant les obstacles ? Comment les pays de la CEDEAO traduisent cette résolution en action ? De quel point a la gamme de méthodes disponibles au niveau communauté élargi ? Dans quelle mesure la résistance des cadres de niveau supérieure reste comme obstacle ? Quels problèmes des ressources humaines restent à résoudre ? Quelles sont les implications pour la couverture universelle, le coût et la pérennisation ?

sessions.sessionDescription:
Panel Objectives:

This FP2020-sponsored panel will highlight examples of success stories of countries that have moved from commitment to action.

Panel Description:

As we close in on 2020 and look ahead to attaining the Sustainable Development Goals by 2030, family planning remains at the top of the global agenda as a best-buy in global development.

The Family Planning 2020 movement and all its partners continue to build on the momentum of the 2017 Family Planning Summit in London, where policymakers, donors, and advocates gathered to recommit to the partnership and discuss our collective efforts to reach the goals set in 2012 and since.

Countries are at the heart of the FP2020 partnership and this panel will feature four diverse countries’ success stories that converge around the shared question – how do countries move from commitment to action and ultimately, progress towards their FP2020 goals?

These success stories will focus on improving the enabling environment for women and girls to access FP and RH services – by renewing a law, expanding financing for universal health coverage and closing the equity gap in age and wealth quintiles.

Implications:

This panel will provide the family planning and SRHR community with key examples of how countries are moving from commitment to action.  For other countries in attendance, it will serve as a learning opportunity of what is driving progress towards FP2020 goals as we all continue towards that shared goal set in 2012 and renewed in 2017.

sessions.sessionDescription: Comment augmenter l’engagement des communautés à promouvoir et à adopter la planification familiale ? Il faut commencer avec les leaders locaux, c’est-à-dire les maires. Dans ce panel, les leaders communautaires représentant des collectivités locales du Bénin et du Burkina Faso, le responsable finances TCI, et des représentants de l’Association Internationale des Maires Francophones partageront leurs expériences en matière de santé de la reproduction et de la planification familiale (SR/PF) dans le contexte du projet The Challenge Initiative (TCI). TCI est un projet financé par la Fondation Bill & Melinda Gates. En Afrique de l’Ouest francophone (AOF) auprès des populations urbaines pauvres dans les neuf pays du Partenariat de Ouagadougou (PO), le TCI vise à offrir un appui technique et financier aux autorités locales pour la conception et la mise en œuvre des initiatives PF locales (dans l’atteinte des objectifs définis dans les plans d’action nationaux PF budgétisés). Les projets de développement parfois visent à servir la population locale sans considération du rôle des maires et d’autres leaders locaux. Le TCI se base fortement sur les leaders locaux et les ressources existantes et encourage les villes à créer dans leurs plans communaux de développement des lignes budgétaires pour la PF. Les maires ont le droit et la responsabilité de considérer et de partager avec la population l’intérêt à adopter la PF. Les maires ont également la responsabilité à mobiliser les ressources (financières et autres) pour complémenter les ressources externes des projets. Ce panel démontre l’approche efficace de TCI en renforçant les capacités des autorités locales. Il s’agit d’une présentation du projet TCI-AOF (comment les autorités locales reçoivent les actions de coaching/plaidoyer de la plateforme TCI-AOF, les intérêts que cela a suscité pour eux, et les dynamiques qu’ils ont développées afin de capter des ressources locales pour leurs différentes villes) ; une présentations des leaders locaux qui feront la lumière sur comment eux-mêmes sont devenus des ambassadeurs de la PF (et de TCI) au point de faire le coaching et d’inspirer d’autres villes à leur emboiter les pas ; la manière dont le coaching continu de la plateforme TCI-AOF contribue au renforcement des capacités des villes dans la gestion efficace et efficiente des ressources des collectivités locales d’une façon générale et des projets de façon particulière ; et l’approche TCI-AOF en collaboration étroite avec l’Association Internationale des Maires Francophones.

sessions.sessionDescription: The objectives of this panel are two-fold: 1) to share measurement innovations with phone follow-up approaches and use of GPS coordinates to construct synthetic respondent panels and for spatial gridded plot sampling, and 2) to examine concordance between matched health facilities and respondents reporting on family planning indicators to a health information system and in sample surveys.  The four presentations represent measurement and monitoring advances from studies in Burkina Faso, Kenya, Nigeria and Uganda.  A phone follow-up with 3,252 females who consented to a PMA2020 survey in Burkina Faso resulted in 55% completion and tested two call approaches, one computer-assisted telephone interviews (CATI) and the other interactive voice response (IVR) with higher interview acceptance and completion rates found in the (randomized) CATI arm.  Matching algorithms were applied to GPS coordinates from 4 PMA survey rounds in Uganda to construct a synthetic cohort of cases interviewed two or more times.  Their responses in the first and second matched rounds were examined for change in FP practice and need.  In the state of Kaduna, Nigeria, GPS-referenced polygons were constructed to overlap with 60 survey cluster boundaries and extant demographic databases that provide estimated population sizes for these polygons were accessed.  The population estimates from one of two databases more closely corresponded with survey-based population estimates for the clusters.  In Kenya data from a sample survey of FP performance indicators for 620 facilities in three counties were compared with 432 matched facilities reporting into the HIS and concordance analyses carried out.  These four monitoring innovations provide promising results on expanding data collection approaches and lessons on data quality improvements.  As a set, they offer the opportunity to expand national and subnational monitoring capabilities in terms of content, frequency and coverage, as an alternative and complement large-scale surveys.  With increased ownership of mobile phones, call centers can obtain longitudinal data from consenting clients and geo-referenced locations offer new means for sampling communities with known probability.  HIS data offer a routine source for monitoring FP utilization but are incomplete and often of unknown quality and coverage.  This panel is aimed at building the foundation for improved data measurement and quality in low-resource settings with low-cost solutions.

sessions.sessionDescription:
Objectives:

  • Describe Self-Care construct and examine women’s ability and right to self-assess and manage their sexual and reproductive health needs, with a focus on recent evidence on tools and practices that make SRH self-care possible.
  • Review international norms and guidelines around sexual and reproductive rights, and task sharing that establishes a strong foundation for self-care and empowerment of women throughout their SRH life course.
  • Highlight new information on SRH products and practices that enable autonomy and self-care.

Description: Women have practiced self-care for their sexual and reproductive health (SRH) for millennia. Today, self-care has become more sophisticated and data-driven, and research has demonstrated that when people are active participants in their own health care, adherence to medication and treatment regimens improves. Evidence from NCDs (i.e. diabetes and hypertension) and HIV and HPV self-testing, have demonstrated the feasibility and necessity of self-care approaches; applying this lens to women’s management of fertility is instructive.  Efforts to facilitate user autonomy and peer support have the potential to advance sexual and reproductive health and rights.  Encouraging self-care where and when appropriate can make health care products and practices more accessible; reinforce internationally agreed upon reproductive rights and self-determination; and help alleviate human resource shortages in health systems by using evidence-based and promising practices. Exciting new developments in contraception and medical abortion—including a growing body of evidence for practices such as contraceptive self-injection, pericoital (“on-demand”) use of oral contraception, and home-based medical abortion—provide an opportunity to refocus attention on this important and evolving approach to improving the health and well-being of women and girls and to empowering them to achieve their SRH intentions.

Research/program/policy implications: Panelists will highlight strategies that program designers, implementers, product developers, and policymakers can deploy to support women’s autonomy and self-care in managing their reproductive health including:

  • Raising awareness of the importance of women’s autonomy in reproductive health decision-making and management of their fertility.
  • Identifying and documenting the array of self-care products and practices across health areas.
  • Building the evidence base to strengthen the design and acceptance of self-care practices by women, providers, and health systems.

sessions.sessionDescription: The 2018 ICFP CEO FPitchfest brings together some of the thought leaders in family planning and reproductive health to compete live in making a compelling case for the most powerful idea they believe will be transformative for the community. Each participant is requested to Tell us something we don’t know now that is going to change the game in reproductive health and family planning in the next 5 years. In under 3 minutes, each will tell the audience about a technological breakthrough, a creative approach, new areas of programming, contraceptive innovations, new ways of measuring progress, or changes in environmental conditions that will be game changing. Each participant, upon request, will be allowed to use only one picture or figure to illustrate the central message. Live audience participation through voting using an app will make this session both substantive and fun. Although we will treat all the presenters as winners, the top 3 will receive a surprise recognition/award from the conference organizers. Ten CEOs from both the North and the South will participate.

sessions.sessionDescription: To drive home the impact of the FP2020 movement and the family planning sector as a whole, this plenary will put the spotlight on high-impact elements of successful national research-based family planning programs. Program outcomes will be viewed through the eyes of both the women and girls able to make their own reproductive decisions as well as the country leaders whose commitments and evidence-based policies are making that possible. Specific programs and investments will be highlighted that focus on reaching country-specific FP2020 goals.
sessions.sessionName: Bending the Curve

sessions.sessionDescription:
The decade of 2010-2020 is becoming a memorable period in the history of family planning (FP) and global development as a whole. With six years elapsed since the FP2020 commitments made during the September 2012 London Summit, the world has already observed a remarkable increase of over 38.8 million additional users of modern contraceptives among women and girls. However, despite this increase, the ambitious FP2020 goal of 120 million additional users by the year 2020 appears difficult to reach given current projections. With two years left, after the International Conference on Family Planning in Kigali, much more can be accomplished as the FP community continues to bend the curve in reaching more who need family planning.

The family planning community has shown that given access to the right resources, best practices, bold policies and new ways of programming, it is capable of achieving more and  continue to bend the curve toward the 2020 goals as well as the SDG 2030 goal of “ensuring universal access to sexual and reproductive health-care services, including for family planning, information and education, and the integration of reproductive health into national strategies and programs”.

Family planning interventions continue to face obstacles related to policies, business as usual approaches, cost-effective financing, disruptions in supply chains, serving key populations such as adolescents and displaced girls and women, and timely reliable measures and documentation for performance and accountability indicators. For this goal to be realized, the next decade will be even more critical. While still focused on ensuring that we reach our FP2020 goals, it is now time, in this conference, which is a gathering of the best and brightest in our community, to begin discussions and consultations Beyond 2020.

The Bill & Melinda Gates Institute for Population and Reproductive Health (GI) will bring together and host representatives from key family planning sectors - governments, donors, civil society organizations, bilateral and multilateral organizations, pharmaceutical and private businesses, and youth rights activists to lead this panel. The Panel will address “Beyond 2020” issues by covering the following topics:

  • Resources and Financing: Changing the future landscape of financing and shifting towards country ownership
  • Positive disruptions in family planning policies and programs
  • Post-2020 mechanisms and accountability

    • This panel presents a unique and timely opportunity for both retro- and prospective explorations of existing donor mechanisms, policy design and implementation frameworks, and performance monitoring and accountability tools. These explorations will allow proper adaptation to major recommended steps to be undertaken beyond 2020 to realize universal access to rights-based family planning by 2030.

    The panel will discuss opportunities to mobilize resources and optimize their use, building on those currently available. The panel will discuss national insurance schemes and other innovative cost-effective models such as conditional cash transfer programs which have been proven to accelerate fertility decline in developing countries. Additionally, the panel will discuss disruptive programming innovations such as The Challenge Initiative’s demand-driven model that has revolutionized family planning programs to meet the needs of the increasing urban poor populations. This model has proven that reshaping the donor landscape and shifting the responsibilities and accountability to local government promotes ownership and improves family planning services to local populations.

    The panelists and attendees will explore other transformational potential approaches to reach women with the most need, ?expand the availability of services to the last-mile populations, increase the range of methods available, broaden evidence-based behavior change, performance monitoring, and accountability, and research and development interventions. Emerging ideas that promote local ownership and local-driven financing such as tapping into local philanthropists, existing resources such as the social security system and potential public-private partnerships, will also be discussed.

    Results of the panel discussion will be compiled and summarized in a brief that will be made available to governments, donors, organizations and private sector institutions for reference. The summary will also be posted on the Gates Institute website. After the 2018 ICFP, the Gates Institute will organize a series of convenings and consultations to further the discussions on the outcomes of this panel, and provide inputs for charting the “Beyond 2020 Agenda”.
sessions.sessionName: Beyond 2020: Thinking Beyond Imagination

presentations.title: Improving quality of family planning services in India: The importance of local advocacy working groups
Practical approaches to improve quality of care: Perspectives from private sector
Power to the people: Social accountability mechanisms to improving quality of services and increase contraceptive use
Gaps and implications to quality of care measurement in family planning program: Learnings from India

sessionChairs.company: Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health

sessions.sessionDescription:
Panel objective:

Panel aims to establish that focused interventions such as advocacy, social accountability, and public-private partnerships can improve public health systems’ ability to provide quality family planning (FP) services. It will also highlight that monitoring and measuring quality needs to be pragmatic and can be integrated in programs.

Panel description:

Improving QoC is difficult. Determining and documenting interventions resulting in improvements in QoC is crucial for the field. Measuring and operationalizing quality are essential to improving QoC and are an underlying theme of this panel. QoC is a right and must be at the center of family planning programs, if FP2020 goals are to be achieved.

Since the infamous and tragic deaths during sterilization in Bilaspur, India, the family planning program is revitalized to give attention to quality. Government of India has emphasized approaches such as fixed day services, maximum number of services per provider, facility readiness, and establishment of district quality assurance committees amongst many others to improve quality and consistency of available services. However, implementation of these approaches remain a challenge with constraints such as availability of trained providers, lack of infrastructure, advocacy at appropriate levels,  accountability, monitoring and commodities.

With these perspectives, panel will share achievements in improving and understanding QoC within the Indian public health system through diverse programmatic and research efforts:

  • ‘Importance of local advocacy working groups’ showcases mobilization of financial and human resources, and policy changes to improve quality of FP services by integrating advocacy in public health systems;
  • ‘Private sector perspectives to QoC’ focuses on the improvements in QoC by simplifying and institutionalizing guidelines/protocols, and providing support to public sector. In addition, it will highlight the difference in quality as defined in policies and guidelines and as understood by service providers;
  • ‘Community Action for Health initiative’ presents improvement in quality and increased contraceptive use by empowering community and elected representatives to monitor and provide direct feedback on the quality and functioning of public health services;
  • ‘Gaps and implications in quality of care’ shares important lessons learnt from large-scale measurement of quality of care work and offer suggestions around need for common understanding between program implementation and monitoring.

    • Research/program/policy implications:

    Panel presentations will share policy and programmatic recommendations and highlight interventions and monitoring frameworks that global reproductive health/family planning stakeholders can replicate, adapt, or integrate to advance progress in quality of care for FP services in their geographies.

presentations.title: Performance Monitoring & Evidence Working Group (PME WG): monitoring progress of the FP2020 movement
Track20: building capacity to produce, use and analyze data in FP2020 countries
Performance Monitoring and Accountability 2020 (PMA2020): contribution, lessons, and way forward

sessions.sessionDescription:
OBJECTIVES

Highlight how FP2020 measurement partners are improving the infrastructure and capacity for generating, reporting and using family planning data, through innovative efforts in data collection, modeling, analysis and dissemination, which have collectively contributed to advances in monitoring progress toward FP2020’s ambitious goals, on the path to the 2030 Sustainable Development Goals.

DESCRIPTION

As a time-bound initiative with an ambitious goal – 120 million additional users of modern methods of family planning by 2020 – FP2020 places great emphasis on measuring progress, and from its inception has been committed to leading a transformation in the global monitoring of family planning data. FP2020 publishes annual, internationally comparable estimates on different dimensions of family planning across 69 focus countries.

This panel of FP2020 measurement partners will discuss how their work is improving the frequency, utility, understanding and use of family planning data for performance management, decision-making and advocacy at the global and country level:

  • The FP2020 Performance Monitoring & Evidence Working Group (PME WG) provides technical advice and support for monitoring progress towards the FP2020 goal, by reporting annually on progress in the 69 FP2020 countries; by advancing measurement and improving understanding of key dimensions of family planning; and by supporting the use of data for decision-making.
  • Track20 works with FP2020 commitment-making countries to produce annual estimates of family planning indicators, and to review national and subnational data to shed light on where gains are being made, where efforts should be reinforced, where investments will have the most impact, and where more data and information are needed.
  • PMA2020 (Performance Monitoring and Accountability 2020) uses mobile technology to support low-cost, rapid-turnaround surveys monitoring key family planning indicators in 11 FP2020 countries. The PMA2020 platform is increasing the frequency of family planning survey data, testing new data collection methods and survey questions, and providing insights into the dynamics of contraceptive use.

IMPLICATIONS

Governments in FP2020 countries have access to more frequent and higher quality data, with increased capacity to analyze this data and distill insights. This enables countries to better monitor family planning program outputs and outcomes, refine family planning strategies, and prioritize interventions for maximum impact. At the same time, advances in data collection, modeling and reporting are improving understanding of contraceptive trends and dynamics, enhancing measurement of key dimensions of family planning (e.g. rights, quality, adolescents/youth, expenditures), and shedding light on where more research, data and analysis are needed.

presentations.title: First-Time Parent Lifestage: A conceptual framework for understanding and contextualizing the complex needs of new parents
Factors influencing use of health services by first-time/young parents: Findings from formative research in Madagascar and Nigeria
Findings for first-time parents from a randomized controlled trial of the Bandebereho gender-transformative couple’s intervention in Rwanda
Lessons learned from an integrated approach to addressing sexual and reproductive health needs of first-time parents in Zinder, Niger

sessions.sessionDescription:
Objectives:

•  To use a socioecological approach to explore the complex factors that shape the First-Time Parent (FTP) lifestage and influence FTP family planning (FP) and maternal and child health (MCH) action;

•   To present approaches and results from programs that integrate FP within a broader response for FTPs.

Description:

There has been growing recognition of the vulnerabilities of FTPs as they navigate through their first experiences with pregnancy, childbirth, and raising a child.  Presenters will share recent FTP programming experience and evidence, building a case for integrating FP within a holistic response for new parents. 

•  The Evidence to Action (E2A) Project will present its FTP Lifestage Framework, laying out the complex health, social and gender factors that shape the experience of new parents.

•  The Maternal and Child Survival Program (MCSP) will share findings from formative research with first-time/young mothers and fathers and key influencers, using a socioecological approach, that explored factors influencing service utilization in Madagascar and Nigeria. Findings will build understanding of FTP needs and highlight implications for holistic, life-course tailored programming.

•  Promundo will share results for FTPs who participated in a couples' intervention integrating FP within a broader health and gender platform in Rwanda.  Data presented will highlight key FTP behavioral outcomes, such as contraceptive use and IPV, and lessons learned in delivering integrated programming for FTPs.

•  Pathfinder will share results from its FTP program in Zinder, Niger.  Data from facilities, qualitative assessments and program evaluation will demonstrate how utilization of MNCH and FP services can be strengthened through an integrated approach.

•   Dr. Chandra-Mouli will highlight the global opportunity to deliver integrated programs for young women and men during this critical lifestage, not only to ensure positive outcomes with the first birth, but also to influence the timing and spacing of future pregnancies. 

Afterward, an audience-panelist discussion will explore opportunities for responding to FTP needs, including challenges and successes of implementing integrated programming. Reflections on elements or models for successful FP integration will conclude the panel.

Implications:

For FTPs, FP is one of multiple, converging issues that shape the transition to parenthood and contribute to poor health outcomes. By better understanding this complex lifestage and packaging FP within a holistic response, programs address FTPs’ immediate needs and influence a lifetime of FP, SRH and MNCH outcomes.  Up-to-date evidence on effective integrated program approaches will help us meet our current goals and catalyze long-term benefits for FTPs and their communities.
sessions.trackName: Integration of family planning into health and development programs
sessions.sessionName: Meeting the Needs of New Parents: A Call for an Integrated FP/MNCH Approach

presentations.title: Unlocking the Potential of Faith-Based Advocacy: How the Mityana Diocese Shepherded Uganda’s First Subnational FP CIP
Faith-led Advocacy Results in First-ever Contraceptive Budget Line in South-Kivu Province of DRC
Subnational CIPs in Tanzania: FBOs Take the Lead
The Young and the Faithful: Localizing Kenya’s FP Commitments Through Budget Advocacy

sessions.sessionDescription:
PANEL OBJECTIVES:

  • Demonstrate that faith-based organizations (FBOs) can effectively engage in high-level SMART policy advocacy, yielding tangible outcomes for family planning (FP);
  • Highlight the challenges of and lessons learned from mobilizing FBOs and religious leaders as FP advocates; and
  • Provide actionable steps for FBOs seeking to ramp up their advocacy efforts, as well as for CSOs looking to  partner with FBOs in advancing shared advocacy agendas.

DESCRIPTION:

Initiatives such as Family Planning 2020 (FP2020) and the Ouagadougou Partnership have increased commitment to FP globally. To sustain this momentum and fulfill the potential of these efforts, it is critical that civil society is fully mobilized as a partner in achieving national FP priorities. As a part of civil society, FBOs can and should play a central role as advocates for FP at national and subnational levels.

FBOs bring credibility and moral authority to the FP conversation, uniquely positioning them to broker support among government, community leaders and other constituencies critical to implementing FP policies, mobilizing funding, and delivering services. As FBOs provide a significant proportion of primary health care services—including reproductive and maternal-newborn care—across sub-Saharan Africa and beyond, sustainability is built-in to their approach to FP service delivery and advocacy. Still, FBOs have not been fully leveraged as vocal advocates for FP, though many are strongly supportive of the cause.

This panel will showcase successful FBO advocacy efforts from four countries—Uganda, the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), Tanzania and Kenya—which were supported by PAI’s Faith + FP Fund. Grounded in the AFP SMART approach, the Fund provides technical and financial support to FBOs in the Global South to hold their governments accountable for meeting FP2020 and Ouagadougou Partnership commitments.

IMPLICATIONS:

This panel will demonstrate that, when armed with the needed expertise and skills, FBOs can be powerful local advocates, foster shared accountability and achieve concrete FP outcomes. From securing local investments in FP to spearheading the development of subnational costed FP strategies, FBOs have made remarkable contributions to the FP policy and funding landscape.

The panelists will discuss how the engagement of religious leaders in FP advocacy can catalyze local action and mitigate opposition to FP. Faith-based advocacy can also help to ensure sustainability of FP progress in many countries due to the role of religion in all aspects of private and public life.
sessions.sessionName: Policy and Funding Change Requires Faith: Results and Lessons From Faith-led Advocacy for Family Planning

presentations.title: Boys need to know this too: Improving puberty awareness and gender equality among very young adolescents in Rwanda
How do you increase vasectomy uptake in Rwanda? Reviewing past trends and current statistics
Bandebereho: A gender-transformative comprehensive intervention to promote sexual and reproductive health, reduce violence, and promote equality among young people and new and expectant parents

sessions.sessionDescription:
Today, more men view family planning as a shared responsibility. Evidence increasingly suggests that unequal gender norms, including rigid notions of masculinity and femininity, shape men’s and women’s behavior and limit the uptake of family planning. Male engagement FP outcomes include improved FP uptake, as well as secondary improvements in relationships:

  • Greater discussion with parents about reproductive health topics in childhood and adolescence;
  • Increased gender equitable attitudes among boys;
  • Improved couple communication;
  • Increased knowledge of family planning methods;
  • Fathers increasing their parenting responsibilities; and,
  • More equitable household decision-making.

Gender transformative interventions help men and boys navigate traditional expectations and fulfill their potential as supportive friends, equitable partners, and loving fathers. Challenging social constructions of masculinity is hard work. Gender transformative interventions similarly support women and girls in understanding how gendered expectations shape their and their partners’ behaviors, and in negotiating and advocating for change towards more empowerment and equality.

USAID’s guidance brief on male engagement in family planning suggests that approaches should reflect men’s diverse range of needs, which change over time and context and that programs should address negative gender norms throughout this process.

Men’s reproductive health programming is at a critical point for growth.  There are a myriad of proven interventions that engage men at discrete points in time, but comprehensive men’s reproductive health programming does not exist. Several male-focused reproductive health interventions were pioneered in Rwanda. These interventions increase fertility and FP knowledge, provide access to permanent methods, and challenge inequitable gender norms at different stages of the life course.

Central to programming at each stage of the life course is the need to combat harmful existing gender constructs of masculinity and perceptions of rigid gender roles. This panel will present three exciting interventions that share approaches to engaging men (and sometimes women) for reproductive health outcomes is tailored to age related contexts. Three panelists will describe approaches to addressing reproductive health content and services for men across four age categories: very early adolescents, young adult men and women, expectant and new fathers and couples, and men interested to limit family size.
sessions.sessionName: Programming Male Engagement Across the Life-Course

Acceptability of self-injection of DMPA-SC in the DRC

authors.company: Reproductive Health Division, Ministry of Health Uganda

sessionChairs.company: Reproductive Health Division, Ministry of Health Uganda

sessions.sessionDescription:
Panel objectives:

  • To demonstrate that self-injection of subcutaneous depot-medroxyprogesterone acetate (DMPA-SC; brand name Sayana Press) is safe and acceptable to women, based on extensive evidence from several countries.
  • To demonstrate that self-injection can improve family planning continuation by women who choose this method, based on new results from Malawi and Uganda.
  • To highlight how researchers and implementers in Ghana, Malawi, DRC, and Uganda have engaged with stakeholders to advance rollout and scale-up of self-injection; and help move the global conversation from a call for more research toward applying research results to self-injection program delivery, including rigorous monitoring and evaluation to answer outstanding questions.  

    • Description: This pre-formed panel will highlight recent evidence generated on the new and innovative contraceptive option of self-injection of DMPA-SC. DMPA-SC has a shorter needle and lower dose compared to intramuscular DMPA and comes prefilled in an all-in-one injection system that simplifies injections for lay health workers and women themselves. DMPA-SC self-injection reduces the frequency that women must return to a health facility or a provider for reinjection, increasing convenience and discretion of contraceptive use. Given these advantages, DMPA-SC self-injection is gaining acceptance in more countries as a way for women to take control of their own fertility; at the same time, stakeholders and providers in many countries still have questions and concerns about the practice and its role in their family planning system and market. The panel will present evidence from countries at different stages of DMPA-SC introduction/scale-up, from earliest (Ghana) to more advanced (Uganda). These presentations will show how family planning policymakers and program implementers, regardless of their countries’ stage of DMPA-SC introduction, can use the evidence generated here to advocate for and deliver self-injection as an additional delivery option for women.

    Research/program/policy implications: This panel will demonstrate the robust evidence base on the safety and acceptability of self-injection, and newer evidence that self-injection can increase continuation among users of injectable contraception. This panel will share evidence with country policymakers, program managers, and implementers that can be used to advocate for or inform planning of self-injection programs and monitoring and evaluation efforts, improving access to injectable contraceptives for women who so desire. Finally, approaches to research utilization that helped smooth the transition from research to practice will be highlighted, and outstanding knowledge gaps and potential strategies for addressing them will be discussed.
sessions.sessionName: Self-Injection of DMPA-SC in Ghana, Malawi, DRC, and Uganda: Increasing Access, Improving Continuation, and Empowering Women

presentations.title: Well Told Story: The power of narrative for reproductive health
Nia brand: The power of purpose and adolescent behavior change
Nivi: The power of identifying consumer intent in reproductive health conversations

sessions.sessionDescription:
Meeting adolescent contraceptive needs requires dynamic demand generation strategies that are appropriate to context, build trust, and capable of empowering young consumers. This panel presents programmatic experience in designing and scaling effective demand generation among adolescents and young women of Kenya. 

Achieving contraceptive uptake involves stages of behavior change in which the consumer refines their self-awareness to discover intent, renew purpose, and shape more powerful narratives. In Kenya, three organizations are implementing demand generation programs that use novel strategies to engage consumers.

Nia is an aspirational menstrual hygiene management brand that helps its adolescent girl customers to access reproductive health answers and service providers via diverse platforms. Equally important, the brand makes women proud and confident, and is a trusted voice for health education. The Nia sanitary pad is a platform on which reproductive information/education is marketed; as pads are sold in retail outlets across Nairobi it has visibility and presence that engages the target audience.

Nivi is a digital health company that bridges the information and access gap that women and girls face in emerging markets. By texting a question or keyword, users gain access to trusted information about women’s health and receive localized and personalized recommendations and referrals to high quality products and servicesthrough Nivi's unique referral engine. Nivi brings together the power of the cloud, the personal touch of a mobile phone, and first-class customer service in a unique solution to enable women and girls to lead healthier lives. 

Well Told Story (WTS) leverages the power of narrative to empower young consumers with new perspectives and agency. Among other products, WTS produces Shujaaz, a story that follows fictional and real youth from different parts of Kenya and Tanzania as they encounter, discuss and resolve challenging life issues. Created in 2010, Shujaaz employs a 360-degree, interactive multimedia platform (a comic, radio, SMS and social media) to promote better health choices and teach marketable skills to millions of East Africans aged 15-24.

The panel will explore each organization's approach to demand generation and share operational insights. By end of the panel, participants will be able:

- identify at least 3 demand generation strategies to engage adolescents on contraceptive services 

- name online and offline approaches that have been deployed in Kenya

- isolate the policy and programmatic challenges and opportunities in deploying demand generation in different markets

presentations.title: For Us and By Us: Enabling Meaningful Youth Leadership in Policy Advocacy in India

sessions.sessionDescription:
Objectives: The goal of this panel is to: 1) share lessons learned from activities in three countries that built the capacity of youth to assess the implementation of youth sexual and reproductive health (SRH) policies and 2) link the activity findings to broader efforts to hold governments accountable to implementing existing policies that aim to improve youth access to contraceptive services and information.

Description: The panelists will discuss how their organizations fostered youth leadership and built the capacity of youth across a continuum of activities: assessing the strength of written policies, gathering data on policy implementation, using the results of the policy assessments to plan advocacy strategies, and advocating for improved policy implementation.

Meredith Pierce will discuss a “Youth Family Planning Policy Scorecard” that measures and compares sixteen countries’ youth family planning policies across eight indicators proven to remove barriers and improve youth access to and use of contraception. The Scorecard’s findings highlight the importance of measuring the extent to which policies are being implemented in countries with strong written policies, such as Burkina Faso and Kenya.

Saïdou Sawadogo and Lucy Kiarie will then share experiences engaging youth in policy implementation assessments and subsequent youth-led policy advocacy efforts in Burkina Faso and Kenya. In both countries, the assessment methodology captured both key stakeholder perspectives and youth experiences. The panelists will share their findings regarding the gaps and progress in youth SRH policy implementation and how they informed the advocacy strategies designed by youth advocates in each country.  

Manasa Priya Vasudevan will discuss her work with a cohort of youth advocates from four states in India that includes: building youth advocates’ knowledge of existing youth SRH policies, empowering youth to identify critical gaps in policy implementation using multiple data sources, generating evidence-based policy recommendations, and creating opportunities for youth-led dialogue.

Research/program/policy implications: Governments have increasingly recognized the importance of involving youth in the creation of policies and programs that affect them. Indeed, many countries have policies that aim to improve youth access to and use of contraception that have been created based on evidence of what works and with input from youth themselves. Actively involving youth in every stage of program design, implementation, and evaluation should extend to engaging youth in assessing the extent to which existing policies are being implemented. Youth should be supported and provide leadership in efforts to hold their national and sub-national governments accountable to following through on their written policy commitments.

Moderator's active engagement discussion for Panel: Equitable access, sustainable investments, and development benefits: investing in family planning for a lifetime of returns

sessions.sessionDescription:
Moderator: Ian Askew, WHO

Panellists: Mike Mbizvo (PC), Elizabeth Sully (GI), Gifty Addico (UNFPA)

Description:

While the internationally agreed upon Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) attest that, “Ensuring healthy lives and promoting the well-being for all at all ages is essential to sustainable development,” substantial efforts need to be made to make this a reality for all. Family planning (FP) is among key interventions available to reduce mortality and improve health related to reproduction, and yet its uptake remains lower than universally needed and is inequitable between and within nations. Research evidence on returns, and subsequent utilization, within a conducive financing environment, is a development imperative.

This first presentation provides an overview of the rationale, benefits and efficiency gains of investment in family planning from a social, health and economic perspective.   The second presentation provides a follow on, bringing to the fore recent data on inequities, as influencing unmet need for family planning, and thus allude to gaps and needs in the context of the global call on leaving no one behind. The third presentation will draw on the evidence presented on the social, economic and health returns associated with family planning, and the need to address inequities, reviewing the case for securing sustainable investment in family planning to ensure the long run success towards SDGs. 

Panel overall objective:

To share research data that reinforces the health and development roles of equitable access and sustainable investments, for family planning:

  • Show the interrelationship between FP and other SDGs;
  • Highlight inequities in FP to underscore where efforts are needed to ensure that no one is left behind in meeting FP and development goals;
  • Critically review the current state of policy and financial commitments to FP and what is needed to ensure sustainable investments.

    • Conclusion

    This panel examines the relationship between family planning in the context of benefits and the SDGs: what the impact is of FP on other development goals, who is currently being left behind in family planning efforts, and what is needed to ensure sustainable financing for FP. The Panel will show how investment in Family planning confers returns that are critical to health and development. 

    Research program and policy implications:

    The three presentations cover a continuum from defining the problem areas, the health and development rationale and, drawing from the next Adding It Up addition, highlight intervention gaps for research and programming in the second presentation, with policy implications and recommendations for domestic and other financing underscored in the third presentation.
