sessions.sessionDescription:
Panel Objectives

  • To share emerging evidence on the roles and responsibilities of men and boys in advancing SRHR and family planning
  • To present on how MenEngage Alliance conducts integrated joint advocacy on key issues regarding family planning and SRHR and how engaging men and boys contributes to strengthened global movement building to advocate for SRHR for all.
  • To generate discussion on how this work can be done in an accountable manner towards women, girls and people of diverse sexual orientation or gender identity.

Description

This session will present the work of MenEngage Alliance and its members/partners on gender transformative approaches to engaging boys and men to challenge stigma, discrimination, attitudes and laws that undermine the fulfilment of SRHR for all. The panelists, from both the Global South and North, will share experiences from initiatives that engage men and boys in key SRHR issues, including equality in responsibility for contraceptive use and family planning, women’s right to choose and access safe and legal abortion, comprehensive sexuality education, ending homophobia and transphobia and increasing men’s access to and use of HIV and other SRH services. The panel will present a comprehensive approach and strategies that MenEngage Alliance members and partners apply including interconnected policy advocacy, the mobilization of youth ‘changemakers’, network building and capacity strengthening, evidence generation and dissemination and strengthening partnerships.

Panelists will present their experiences of implementing gender-transformative programming and campaigns to engage men in SRHR, focusing specifically on emerging evidence, promising practices and lessons learned. They will discuss engaging men and boys across the socio-ecological model, how the engagement of individual boys and men can link to efforts to transform attitudes, norms, institutions and policies, and how the engagement of men and boys can contribute to strengthening global movement building to advance SRHR for all. The panel will also have a specific focus on accountability and how this work can be done in a way that is fully accountable to, and in collaboration with, women’s rights and SRHR organizations.

Research/program/policy implications

The panel seeks to strengthen understanding of gender transformative, feminist informed and rights-based approaches and interventions inclusive of a ‘men and masculinities’ perspective, to advance SRHR among researchers, practitioners and policymakers and contribute to the global knowledge base for this work. Among the panelists we will also have researchers and theorists who have invested their professional life in creating pragmatic theory of change to underpin this work globally.

sessions.sessionDescription:
Panel objectives:

There is growing recognition that achievement of the FP2020 goal requires paying attention to quality of care.  The rationale is that a focus on quality of care will help attract new users while also ensuring that existing users receive the necessary support to continue contraception.  Furthermore, as countries move towards rights-based family planning programming, quality of care will be an integral component of service design and implementation. 

The presentations on this panel will examine different ways of measuring quality using different data sources and methods and present findings from multiple settings that reflect the service environment and client experience.  The overall objective is to distill lessons learnt to inform adoption of a uniform way of measuring quality. 

Description:  

Indicators are required for multiple purposes ranging from describing existing services, monitoring quality over time, assessing effect of interventions to documenting client outcomes of health and wellbeing.  Quality needs to be measured at the policy level to measure intent of programs to offer good quality services, at the service delivery channel level to measure readiness to offer quality care, at the client-provider interaction level to measure care provided, and at the client level to measure client satisfaction with services received and subsequent contraceptive behaviors. 

Our panel includes four thought-provoking presentations on measures of quality that have been applied at the readiness, client-provider interaction, and client levels.  PMA2020 will present trends of service readiness using facility surveys and care received and women’s perspectives from population-based surveys.  The DHS Program will present data from Service Provision Assessment (SPA) surveys on alternate measures of readiness of facilities, services offered and received by clients.  Metrics for Management will present the relationships between structural and process quality assessed at the facility, Method Information Index (MII) and discontinuation. The Population Council will present findings of care provided and client contraceptive continuation.

The session will be moderated by Jason Bremner, Director, Data and Performance Management, FP2020. 

Research/program/policy implications:

A focus on quality of care implies putting the client at the center of service delivery.  It therefore follows that performance indicators need to align with the service delivery process.  As family planning programs implement rights-based services at scale, indicators of quality of care that can be uniformly applied across different health systems are needed.

sessions.sessionDescription:
Objectives:

The participants will understand the role that faith leaders and faith communities are playing in improving contraceptive access and uptake.

The participants will be able to ask questions to better understand how family planning programs could benefit from a faith outreach component and dialogue around misperceptions around how faith communities respond to family planning messages.

The participants will leave the session with the ability to share the actions that faith leaders are taking to advocate for family planning policies and services in their communities and to promote engagement with faith leaders in their own programs.

Background & Methods: In sub-Saharan Africa, 85-90% of people identify religion as very important and there are 225 million women around the world with an unmet need of family planning. In many countries, faith-based organizations provide large percentages of health care, especially in rural areas. Faith and religious leaders are cultural gatekeepers and are essential partners to empower their organizations and churches to be comfortable with family planning, and to ensure community members talk about family planning openly and will access services. To counter misunderstanding of the role and opinions of religious leaders and to show public support, this session will emphasize discussion on what religious leaders have done well and what they could do better. Representatives from the Ghana Muslim Family Counselling Services, Catholics for Reproductive Health (C4RH) in the Philippines, the Churches Health Association of Zambia (CHAZ), and World Vision Kenya will share their experiences using a Fishbowl Format (inner circle of speakers, larger outside circle of attendees, and the inner circle will change and expand as the conversation continues). This format is meant to ensure dynamic participation going beyond a more traditional presentation approach.

Results: Advocacy efforts will highlight four regions of the world and four different faith engagement experiences. GFCS will highlight their advocacy efforts of FP into the national health insurance program; CHAZ will talk about how they trained RLs from 16 denominations to advocate for FP nationally via radio, tv and with the MoH; C4RH will focus on how they engaged 500 members and volunteers in their activities and campaigns about the RH law throughout the country and formation of an interfaith network; and WV Kenya will focus on their efforts to train and mobilize 136 RLs in Siaya County who formed 64 Congressional Hope Action Teams to refer 6,086 women to a facility for FP services through their Channels of Hope methodology.

sessions.sessionDescription:
Description

Behavioral economics (BE) is an approach to unpack decision-making and behavior and design impactful solutions. Recently, BE piqued interest as a promising social and behavior change (SBC) tool in family planning and reproductive health (FP/RH). Nobel Prizes for BE and successes across environment[1][2], finance[3], and education[4] sectors have built momentum for BE, resulting in investments from Hewlett Foundation, Gates Foundation, World Bank, and USAID, posing the question – can BE help tackle FP/RH challenges?

This panel will respond by sharing the latest research and experimental results of early adopters’ BE application to FP/RH. Pathfinder International will share behavioral insights of FP/RH behaviors in Bangladesh, Ethiopia, and Burkina Faso. World Bank will share results from integrating developmental science and BE improving adolescent FP/RH outcomes in Cameroon. Marie Stopes International will present randomized controlled trials (RCT) results for post-abortion FP in Nepal and RH e-coupon redemption in Uganda. JSI will present RCT results reducing injectable discontinuation in Ethiopia. Tulane University, which evaluated Hewlett Foundation’s investment for BE in FP/RH, will moderate the panel.

Objectives

  • Build capacity for BE as an SBC tool in FP/RH by sharing successes and failures; and,
  • Discuss opportunities and challenges of applying BE to FP/RH to shape future SBC programming.

    • Research and Program Implications

    Persistence of intractable FP/RH challenges calls for additional SBC tools, like BE, to advance the sector. BE research insights drive innovative design and show impactful, cost-effective results, which complement existing programming. However, despite initial successes, challenges show BE application can and should be adapted to improve future SBC programming.

     

    [1] Allcott, H. (2011). Social norms and energy conservation. Journal of Public Economics, 95(9–10), 1082–1095. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jpubeco.2011.03.003

    [2] Datta, Saugato; Miranda Montero, Juan Jose; Zoratto, Laura De Castro; Calvo-Gonzalez, Oscar; Darlingm, Matthew; Lorenzana, Karina Josephine Orduna. 2015. Washington, D.C. : World Bank Group. http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/809801468001190306/A-behavioral-approach-to-water-conservation-evidence-from-Costa-Rica

    [3] Benartzi, S., & Thaler, R. H. (2007). Heuristics and Biases in Retirement Savings Behavior. Journal of Economic Perspectives, 21(3), 81–104. https://doi.org/10.1257/jep.21.3.81

    [4] Bettinger, E., Long, B. T., Oreopoulos, P., & Sanbonmatsu, L. (2009). The Role of Simplification and Information in College Decisions: Results from the H&R Block FAFSA Experiment. National Bureau of Economic Research. https://doi.org/10.3386/w15361

sessions.sessionDescription:
Panel objectives       

  • Share examples and evidence of how mobile phones can be used to support family planning and reproductive health
  • Highlight the potential increased risk of intimate partner violence as a result of using mobile phones to support reproductive health
  • Share strategies designed to mitigate risks of mobile phone interventions for reproductive health
  • Discuss how to ensure risks are measured effectively when evaluating mobile phone interventions

Description

Despite the promise of mobile phones to increase access to family planning and reproductive health information and services, experiences from the field have demonstrated that users of these interventions could face unanticipated harm for example because of stigma around family planning or abortion and patriarchal norms around control of female fertility. Given the potential for harm, it is important to consider risks in the design phase, and develop interventions that explicitly consider user-preferences about risk-mitigation. The panel will start with details of a randomised controlled trial of interactive voice mobile phone messages designed to support family planning use in Bangladesh that resulted in an increase in intimate partner violence. The second presentation describes a trial of a similar intervention in Cambodia where no negative effects were found; however no specific violence measurement was included. Issues related to measurement of adverse outcomes will be discussed. The third and fourth presentations will focus on strategies to mitigate potential risks among a range of populations and settings during the design and development of mobile phone reproductive health interventions. We will share learnings from the design process and resulting safety features of mobile phone interventions developed for populations, including adolescents and sex workers, in five countries. Lastly, we will present findings from formative research in five contexts on user preferences around privacy and security features in smartphone applications, and will share lessons learned in how to incorporate the results of this research into the application design process.

Research/program/policy implications

While promising knowledge and empowerment for vulnerable populations, the potential for harm from digital health interventions for family planning and reproductive health must be taken into account. Research is just beginning to identify how interpersonal violence may be catalyzed by mobile phone family planning messages, but formative research and strategic, user-centered design can help to mitigate any potential harm. Future evaluations of digital health interventions on this topic need to routinely monitor possible negative impacts using measures of interpersonal violence.

sessions.sessionDescription:
Overall Panel Objectives:

  • Introduce the concept of a visibility and analytics network and the Global Family Planning VAN (Global FP VAN)
  • Explore Global FP VAN implementation across four components: people, process, technology, and policy
  • Present early findings from current Global FP VAN pilot period and perspectives on stakeholder coordination, governance, process transformation around data management, data sharing, and technology system selection

Description of the Panel Overall:

Data visibility and evidence-based decision-making are buzz words of the day in the global health supply chain world. But what does it take to get there and how can we use these ideas to support contraceptive security? This panel will unpack the basics of a new Reproductive Health Supplies Coalition (RHSC)-managed initiative to increase supply chain visibility through a Global FP VAN. The panel will explain this initiative in the context of RHSC’s history and highlight the recurring challenges it is trying to resolve. Presentations will then explore how the Global FP VAN is bringing together people, policy, processes, and technology in innovative ways to transform how the family planning community responds to supply challenges and makes decisions together. Each panelist will explore one of these themes:

  • People and governance – coordinating multiple players across the supply chain in an active network that uses the same data platform to make joint decisions about product flow into countries
  • Policy and data sharing – establishing multilateral agreements to overcome barriers to data sharing
  • Process and data management – moving from multiple coordination groups to an integrated process, especially around data management
  • Technology and system selection – moving from multiple siloed tools to one virtual, collaborative platform

The panel will highlight how investing in improved use of shared global and country-level supply chain data through technology, combined with effective people, processes, and policies, can transform how governments, donors, manufacturers, and partners coordinate to maximize use of available resources and improve access to family planning products.

 Research/program/policy implications: Creating a single global platform for family planning data and coordinated decision-making has been at the forefront of conversations on improving contraceptive security for years. The Global FP VAN pilot results will determine whether the investment required to establish a Global FP VAN is worth the resulting benefits. If the pilot is deemed successful, it will become a longer-term initiative where the platform will be expanded to scale over time to cover more countries, products, and manufacturers.

sessions.sessionDescription: The closing ceremony will highlight key moments from the 2018 ICFP, recognize participant achievements, and inspire attendees with energy and vision for the future of family planning. Statements will be made by members of the Rwandan Parliament, Youth Delegation, Faith Leaders, and the Scientific Sub-Committee. Top prizes will be awarded for top posters. Winners will be announced for the Packard Quality Innovation Challenge and the Excellence in Leadership for Family Planning (EXCELL) Awards. The conference will conclude with a special presentation and performance by youth and special guests.
sessions.sessionName: Closing Ceremony Luncheon
